      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Justice of a Righteous God
      content: '  Then another message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy do you quote this proverb concerning the land of Israel:
        \u2018The parents have eaten sour grapes, but their children\u2019s mouths
        pucker at the taste\u2019? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        you will not quote this proverb anymore in Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For all people are mine to judge\u2014both parents and children alike.
        And this is my rule: The person who sins is the one who will die.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSuppose a certain man is righteous and does what is just and
        right. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He does not feast in the mountains before Israel\u2019s idols[[COMMENT(0)]]
        or worship them. He does not commit adultery or have intercourse with a woman
        during her menstrual period. "
      comments:
      - number: '18:6 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung; also in 18:12, 15.
    - title: 
      content: 'He is a merciful creditor, not keeping the items given as security
        by poor debtors. He does not rob the poor but instead gives food to the hungry
        and provides clothes for the needy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He grants loans without interest, stays away from injustice, is honest
        and fair when judging others, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and faithfully obeys my decrees and regulations. Anyone who does
        these things is just and will surely live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut suppose that man has a son who grows up to be a robber
        or murderer and refuses to do what is right. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And that son does all the evil things his father would never do\u2014he
        worships idols on the mountains, commits adultery, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'oppresses the poor and helpless, steals from debtors by refusing
        to let them redeem their security, worships idols, commits detestable sins, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and lends money at excessive interest. Should such a sinful person
        live? No! He must die and must take full blame.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut suppose that sinful son, in turn, has a son who sees his
        father\u2019s wickedness and decides against that kind of life. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This son refuses to worship idols on the mountains and does not commit
        adultery. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He does not exploit the poor, but instead is fair to debtors and
        does not rob them. He gives food to the hungry and provides clothes for the
        needy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He helps the poor,[[COMMENT(0)]] does not lend money at interest,
        and obeys all my regulations and decrees. Such a person will not die because
        of his father\u2019s sins; he will surely live. "
      comments:
      - number: '18:17 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>He refuses to do evil.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "But the father will die for his many sins\u2014for being cruel, robbing
        people, and doing what was clearly wrong among his people.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201C\u2018What?\u2019 you ask. \u2018Doesn\u2019t the child pay
        for the parent\u2019s sins?\u2019 No! For if the child does what is just
        and right and keeps my decrees, that child will surely live. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The person who sins is the one who will die. The child will not be
        punished for the parent\u2019s sins, and the parent will not be punished
        for the child\u2019s sins. Righteous people will be rewarded for their own
        righteous behavior, and wicked people will be punished for their own wickedness. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if wicked people turn away from all their sins and begin to obey
        my decrees and do what is just and right, they will surely live and not die. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All their past sins will be forgotten, and they will live because
        of the righteous things they have done.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo you think that I like to see wicked people die? says the
        Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Of course not! I want them to turn
        from their wicked ways and live. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'However, if righteous people turn from their righteous behavior and
        start doing sinful things and act like other sinners, should they be allowed
        to live? No, of course not! All their righteous acts will be forgotten, and
        they will die for their sins.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYet you say, \u2018The Lord isn\u2019t doing what\u2019s right!\u2019
        Listen to me, O people of Israel. Am I the one not doing what\u2019s right,
        or is it you? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When righteous people turn from their righteous behavior and start
        doing sinful things, they will die for it. Yes, they will die because of
        their sinful deeds. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And if wicked people turn from their wickedness, obey the law, and
        do what is just and right, they will save their lives. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will live because they thought it over and decided to turn from
        their sins. Such people will not die. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And yet the people of Israel keep saying, \u2018The Lord isn\u2019t
        doing what\u2019s right!\u2019 O people of Israel, it is you who are not
        doing what\u2019s right, not I.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, I will judge each of you, O people of Israel, according
        to your actions, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Repent,
        and turn from your sins. Don\u2019t let them destroy you! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Put all your rebellion behind you, and find yourselves a new heart
        and a new spirit. For why should you die, O people of Israel? '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "A Funeral Song for Israel\u2019s Kings"
      content: "  \u201CSing this funeral song for the princes of Israel:  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat is your mother?A lioness among lions!She lay down among
        the young lionsand reared her cubs.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'She raised one of her cubsto become a strong young lion.He learned
        to hunt and devour prey,and he became a man-eater.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the nations heard about him,and he was trapped in their pit.They
        led him away with hooksto the land of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen the lioness sawthat her hopes for him were gone,she took
        another of her cubsand taught him to be a strong young lion.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He prowled among the other lionsand stood out among them in his strength.He
        learned to hunt and devour prey,and he, too, became a man-eater.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He demolished fortresses[[COMMENT(0)]]and destroyed their towns and
        cities.Their farms were desolated,and their crops were destroyed.The land
        and its people trembled in fearwhen they heard him roar.  '
      comments:
      - number: '19:7 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>He knew widows.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the armies of the nations attacked him,surrounding him from
        every direction.They threw a net over himand captured him in their pit.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'With hooks, they dragged him into a cageand brought him before the
        king of Babylon.They held him in captivity,so his voice could never again
        be heardon the mountains of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYour mother was like a vineplanted by the water\u2019s edge.It
        had lush, green foliagebecause of the abundant water.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Its branches became strong\u2014strong enough to be a ruler\u2019s
        scepter.It grew very tall,towering above all others.It stood out because
        of its heightand its many lush branches.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the vine was uprooted in furyand thrown down to the ground.The
        desert wind dried up its fruitand tore off its strong branches,so that it
        witheredand was destroyed by fire.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now the vine is transplanted to the wilderness,where the ground is
        hard and dry.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Rebellion of Israel
      content: "  On August 14,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the seventh year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s
        captivity, some of the leaders of Israel came to request a message from the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. They sat down in front of me to wait for his
        reply. "
      comments:
      - number: '20:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>In the fifth month, on the tenth day, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was August 14, 591 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, tell the leaders of Israel, \u2018This is what
        the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: How dare you come to ask
        me for a message? As surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        I will tell you nothing!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, bring charges against them and condemn them. Make
        them realize how detestable the sins of their ancestors really were. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Give them this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        When I chose Israel\u2014when I revealed myself to the descendants of Jacob
        in Egypt\u2014I took a solemn oath that I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        would be their God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I took a solemn oath that day that I would bring them out of Egypt
        to a land I had discovered and explored for them\u2014a good land, a land
        flowing with milk and honey, the best of all lands anywhere. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I said to them, \u2018Each of you, get rid of the vile images
        you are so obsessed with. Do not defile yourselves with the idols[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of Egypt, for I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:7 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung; also in 20:8, 16, 18, 24, 31, 39.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut they rebelled against me and would not listen. They did
        not get rid of the vile images they were obsessed with, or forsake the idols
        of Egypt. Then I threatened to pour out my fury on them to satisfy my anger
        while they were still in Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I didn\u2019t do it, for I acted to protect the honor of my name.
        I would not allow shame to be brought on my name among the surrounding nations
        who saw me reveal myself by bringing the Israelites out of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I brought them out of Egypt and led them into the wilderness. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There I gave them my decrees and regulations so they could find life
        by keeping them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I gave them my Sabbath days of rest as a sign between them and
        me. It was to remind them that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, who
        had set them apart to be holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut the people of Israel rebelled against me, and they refused
        to obey my decrees there in the wilderness. They wouldn\u2019t obey my regulations
        even though obedience would have given them life. They also violated my Sabbath
        days. So I threatened to pour out my fury on them, and I made plans to utterly
        consume them in the wilderness. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But again I held back in order to protect the honor of my name before
        the nations who had seen my power in bringing Israel out of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But I took a solemn oath against them in the wilderness. I swore
        I would not bring them into the land I had given them, a land flowing with
        milk and honey, the most beautiful place on earth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For they had rejected my regulations, refused to follow my decrees,
        and violated my Sabbath days. Their hearts were given to their idols. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nevertheless, I took pity on them and held back from destroying them
        in the wilderness.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen I warned their children not to follow in their parents\u2019
        footsteps, defiling themselves with their idols. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God,\u2019 I told
        them. \u2018Follow my decrees, pay attention to my regulations, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and keep my Sabbath days holy, for they are a sign to remind you
        that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut their children, too, rebelled against me. They refused
        to keep my decrees and follow my regulations, even though obedience would
        have given them life. And they also violated my Sabbath days. So again I
        threatened to pour out my fury on them in the wilderness. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nevertheless, I withdrew my judgment against them to protect the
        honor of my name before the nations that had seen my power in bringing them
        out of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But I took a solemn oath against them in the wilderness. I swore
        I would scatter them among all the nations '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'because they did not obey my regulations. They scorned my decrees
        by violating my Sabbath days and longing for the idols of their ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I gave them over to worthless decrees and regulations that would
        not lead to life. '
      comments: []
    - title: Judgment and Restoration
      content: "I let them pollute themselves[[COMMENT(0)]] with the very gifts I
        had given them, and I allowed them to give their firstborn children as offerings
        to their gods\u2014so I might devastate them and remind them that I alone
        am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:25-26 '
        content: Or <b>I gave them worthless decrees and regulations. . . . I polluted
          them.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, son of man, give the people of Israel this message
        from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: Your ancestors continued
        to blaspheme and betray me, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'for when I brought them into the land I had promised them, they offered
        sacrifices on every high hill and under every green tree they saw! They roused
        my fury as they offered up sacrifices to their gods. They brought their perfumes
        and incense and poured out their liquid offerings to them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I said to them, \u2018What is this high place where you are going?\u2019
        (This kind of pagan shrine has been called Bamah\u2014\u2018high place\u2019\u2014ever
        since.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, give the people of Israel this message from the
        Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: Do you plan to pollute yourselves
        just as your ancestors did? Do you intend to keep prostituting yourselves
        by worshiping vile images? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For when you offer gifts to them and give your little children to
        be burned as sacrifices,[[COMMENT(0)]] you continue to pollute yourselves
        with idols to this day. Should I allow you to ask for a message from me,
        O people of Israel? As surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        I will tell you nothing.  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:31 '
        content: Or <b>and make your little children pass through the fire.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou say, \u2018We want to be like the nations all around us,
        who serve idols of wood and stone.\u2019 But what you have in mind will never
        happen. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        I will rule over you with an iron fist in great anger and with awesome power. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And in anger I will reach out with my strong hand and powerful arm,
        and I will bring you back[[COMMENT(0)]] from the lands where you are scattered. '
      comments:
      - number: '20:34 '
        content: 'Greek version reads <b>I will welcome you. </b>Compare 2 Cor 6:17.  '
    - title: 
      content: 'I will bring you into the wilderness of the nations, and there I
        will judge you face to face. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will judge you there just as I did your ancestors in the wilderness
        after bringing them out of Egypt, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will examine you carefully and hold you to the terms of the covenant. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will purge you of all those who rebel and revolt against me. I
        will bring them out of the countries where they are in exile, but they will
        never enter the land of Israel. Then you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs for you, O people of Israel, this is what the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Go right ahead and worship your idols,
        but sooner or later you will obey me and will stop bringing shame on my holy
        name by worshiping idols. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For on my holy mountain, the great mountain of Israel, says the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the people of Israel will someday worship me,
        and I will accept them. There I will require that you bring me all your offerings
        and choice gifts and sacrifices. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I bring you home from exile, you will be like a pleasing sacrifice
        to me. And I will display my holiness through you as all the nations watch. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then when I have brought you home to the land I promised with a solemn
        oath to give to your ancestors, you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You will look back on all the ways you defiled yourselves and will
        hate yourselves because of the evil you have done. '
      comments: []
    - title: Judgment against the Negev
      content: "You will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, O people
        of Israel, when I have honored my name by treating you mercifully in spite
        of your wickedness. I, the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments:
      - number: '20:45 '
        content: '  Verses 20:45-49 are numbered 21:1-5 in Hebrew text.  '
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn and face the south[[COMMENT(0)]] and speak
        out against it; prophesy against the brushlands of the Negev. "
      comments:
      - number: '20:46 '
        content: Hebrew <b>toward Teman.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Tell the southern wilderness, \u2018This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Hear the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! I will set you on
        fire, and every tree, both green and dry, will be burned. The terrible flames
        will not be quenched and will scorch everything from south to north. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And everyone in the world will see that I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have set this fire. It will not be put out.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Sword of Judgment"
      content: '    [[COMMENT(0)]]Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments:
      - number: '21:1 '
        content: '  Verses 21:1-32 are numbered 21:6-37 in Hebrew text.  '
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn and face Jerusalem and prophesy against Israel
        and her sanctuaries. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Tell her, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        I am your enemy, O Israel, and I am about to unsheath my sword to destroy
        your people\u2014the righteous and the wicked alike. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, I will cut off both the righteous and the wicked! I will draw
        my sword against everyone in the land from south to north. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Everyone in the world will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        My sword is in my hand, and it will not return to its sheath until its work
        is finished.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, groan before the people! Groan before them with
        bitter anguish and a broken heart. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they ask why you are groaning, tell them, \u2018I groan because
        of the terrifying news I have heard. When it comes true, the boldest heart
        will melt with fear; all strength will disappear. Every spirit will faint;
        strong knees will become as weak as water. And the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: It is coming! It\u2019s on its way!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to me, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give the people this message from the Lord:\u201CA
        sword, a swordis being sharpened and polished.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It is sharpened for terrible slaughterand polished to flash like
        lightning!Now will you laugh?Those far stronger than you have fallen beneath
        its power![[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:10 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, the sword is now being sharpened and polished;it is being prepared
        for the executioner.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, cry out and wail;pound your thighs in anguish,for
        that sword will slaughter my people and their leaders\u2014everyone will
        die!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It will put them all to the test.What chance do they have?[[COMMENT(0)]]says
        the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:13 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy to themand clap your hands.Then take the
        sword and brandish it twice,even three times,to symbolize the great massacre,the
        great massacre facing them on every side.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Let their hearts melt with terror,for the sword glitters at every
        gate.It flashes like lightningand is polished for slaughter!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'O sword, slash to the right,then slash to the left,wherever you will,wherever
        you want.  '
      comments: []
    - title: "Omens for Babylon\u2019s King"
      content: "I, too, will clap my hands,and I will satisfy my fury.I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have spoken!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, make a map and trace two routes on it for the sword
        of Babylon\u2019s king to follow. Put a signpost on the road that comes out
        of Babylon where the road forks into two\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'one road going to Ammon and its capital, Rabbah, and the other to
        Judah and fortified Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of Babylon now stands at the fork, uncertain whether to
        attack Jerusalem or Rabbah. He calls his magicians to look for omens. They
        cast lots by shaking arrows from the quiver. They inspect the livers of animal
        sacrifices. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The omen in his right hand says, \u2018Jerusalem!\u2019 With battering
        rams his soldiers will go against the gates, shouting for the kill. They
        will put up siege towers and build ramps against the walls. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people of Jerusalem will think it is a false omen, because of
        their treaty with the Babylonians. But the king of Babylon will remind the
        people of their rebellion. Then he will attack and capture them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Again and again you remind me of your sin and your guilt. You don\u2019t
        even try to hide it! In everything you do, your sins are obvious for all
        to see. So now the time of your punishment has come!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CO you corrupt and wicked prince of Israel, your final day of
        reckoning is here! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:\u201CTake
        off your jeweled crown,for the old order changes.Now the lowly will be exalted,and
        the mighty will be brought down.  "
      comments: []
    - title: A Message for the Ammonites
      content: 'Destruction! Destruction!I will surely destroy the kingdom.And it
        will not be restored until the one appearswho has the right to judge it.Then
        I will hand it over to him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd now, son of man, prophesy concerning the Ammonites and
        their mockery. Give them this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CA
        sword, a swordis drawn for your slaughter.It is polished to destroy,flashing
        like lightning!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your prophets have given false visions,and your fortune-tellers have
        told lies.The sword will fall on the necks of the wickedfor whom the day
        of final reckoning has come.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow return the sword to its sheath,for in your own country,the
        land of your birth,I will pass judgment upon you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will pour out my fury on youand blow on you with the fire of my
        anger.I will hand you over to cruel menwho are skilled in destruction.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Sins of Jerusalem
      content: '  Now this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, are you ready to judge Jerusalem? Are you ready
        to judge this city of murderers? Publicly denounce her detestable sins, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and give her this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        O city of murderers, doomed and damned\u2014city of idols,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        filthy and foul\u2014 "
      comments:
      - number: '22:3 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung; also in 22:4.
    - title: 
      content: 'you are guilty because of the blood you have shed. You are defiled
        because of the idols you have made. Your day of destruction has come! You
        have reached the end of your years. I will make you an object of mockery
        throughout the world. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'O infamous city, filled with confusion, you will be mocked by people
        far and near.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEvery leader in Israel who lives within your walls is bent
        on murder. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Fathers and mothers are treated with contempt. Foreigners are forced
        to pay for protection. Orphans and widows are wronged and oppressed among
        you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You despise my holy things and violate my Sabbath days of rest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'People accuse others falsely and send them to their death. You are
        filled with idol worshipers and people who do obscene things. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Men sleep with their fathers\u2019 wives and force themselves on
        women who are menstruating. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Within your walls live men who commit adultery with their neighbors\u2019
        wives, who defile their daughters-in-law, or who rape their own sisters. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There are hired murderers, loan racketeers, and extortioners everywhere.
        They never even think of me and my commands, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut now I clap my hands in indignation over your dishonest
        gain and bloodshed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'How strong and courageous will you be in my day of reckoning? I,
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken, and I will do what I said. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will scatter you among the nations and purge you of your wickedness. '
      comments: []
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Refining Furnace"
      content: "And when I have been dishonored among the nations because of you,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:16 '
        content: As in one Hebrew manuscript and Greek and Syriac versions; Masoretic
          Text reads <b>when you have been dishonored among the nations.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, the people of Israel are the worthless slag that
        remains after silver is smelted. They are the dross that is left over\u2014a
        useless mixture of copper, tin, iron, and lead. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So tell them, \u2018This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Because you are all worthless slag, I will bring you to my crucible
        in Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Just as silver, copper, iron, lead, and tin are melted down in a
        furnace, I will melt you down in the heat of my fury. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will gather you together and blow the fire of my anger upon you, '
      comments: []
    - title: "The Sins of Israel\u2019s Leaders"
      content: "and you will melt like silver in fierce heat. Then you will know
        that I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have poured out my fury on you.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Again a message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give the people of Israel this message: In the
        day of my indignation, you will be like a polluted land, a land without rain. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your princes[[COMMENT(0)]] plot conspiracies just as lions stalk
        their prey. They devour innocent people, seizing treasures and extorting
        wealth. They make many widows in the land. '
      comments:
      - number: '22:25 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>prophets.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Your priests have violated my instructions and defiled my holy things.
        They make no distinction between what is holy and what is not. And they do
        not teach my people the difference between what is ceremonially clean and
        unclean. They disregard my Sabbath days so that I am dishonored among them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Your leaders are like wolves who tear apart their victims. They actually
        destroy people\u2019s lives for money! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And your prophets cover up for them by announcing false visions and
        making lying predictions. They say, \u2018My message is from the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,\u2019 when the <smallcaps>Lord </smallcaps>hasn\u2019t
        spoken a single word to them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even common people oppress the poor, rob the needy, and deprive foreigners
        of justice.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI looked for someone who might rebuild the wall of righteousness
        that guards the land. I searched for someone to stand in the gap in the wall
        so I wouldn\u2019t have to destroy the land, but I found no one. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Adultery of Two Sisters
      content: '  This message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, once there were two sisters who were daughters
        of the same mother. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They became prostitutes in Egypt. Even as young girls, they allowed
        men to fondle their breasts. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The older girl was named Oholah, and her sister was Oholibah. I married
        them, and they bore me sons and daughters. I am speaking of Samaria and Jerusalem,
        for Oholah is Samaria and Oholibah is Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen Oholah lusted after other lovers instead of me, and she
        gave her love to the Assyrian officers. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They were all attractive young men, captains and commanders dressed
        in handsome blue, charioteers driving their horses. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And so she prostituted herself with the most desirable men of Assyria,
        worshiping their idols[[COMMENT(0)]] and defiling herself. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:7 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung; also in 23:30, 37, 39, 49.
    - title: 
      content: 'For when she left Egypt, she did not leave her spirit of prostitution
        behind. She was still as lewd as in her youth, when the Egyptians slept with
        her, fondled her breasts, and used her as a prostitute.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd so I handed her over to her Assyrian lovers, whom she desired
        so much. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They stripped her, took away her children as their slaves, and then
        killed her. After she received her punishment, her reputation was known to
        every woman in the land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYet even though Oholibah saw what had happened to Oholah, her
        sister, she followed right in her footsteps. And she was even more depraved,
        abandoning herself to her lust and prostitution. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She fawned over all the Assyrian officers\u2014those captains and
        commanders in handsome uniforms, those charioteers driving their horses\u2014all
        of them attractive young men. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I saw the way she was going, defiling herself just like her older
        sister.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen she carried her prostitution even further. She fell in
        love with pictures that were painted on a wall\u2014pictures of Babylonian[[COMMENT(0)]]
        military officers, outfitted in striking red uniforms. "
      comments:
      - number: '23:14 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldean.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Handsome belts encircled their waists, and flowing turbans crowned
        their heads. They were dressed like chariot officers from the land of Babylonia.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:15 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldea; </b>also in 23:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'When she saw these paintings, she longed to give herself to them,
        so she sent messengers to Babylonia to invite them to come to her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they came and committed adultery with her, defiling her in the
        bed of love. After being defiled, however, she rejected them in disgust.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn the same way, I became disgusted with Oholibah and rejected
        her, just as I had rejected her sister, because she flaunted herself before
        them and gave herself to satisfy their lusts. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yet she turned to even greater prostitution, remembering her youth
        when she was a prostitute in Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She lusted after lovers with genitals as large as a donkey\u2019s
        and emissions like those of a horse. "
      comments: []
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Judgment of Oholibah"
      content: 'And so, Oholibah, you relived your former days as a young girl in
        Egypt, when you first allowed your breasts to be fondled.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, Oholibah, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will send your lovers against you from every direction\u2014those
        very nations from which you turned away in disgust. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the Babylonians will come with all the Chaldeans from Pekod and
        Shoa and Koa. And all the Assyrians will come with them\u2014handsome young
        captains, commanders, chariot officers, and other high-ranking officers,
        all riding their horses. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will all come against you from the north[[COMMENT(0)]] with
        chariots, wagons, and a great army prepared for attack. They will take up
        positions on every side, surrounding you with men armed with shields and
        helmets. And I will hand you over to them for punishment so they can do with
        you as they please. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:24 '
        content: As in Greek version; the meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'I will turn my jealous anger against you, and they will deal harshly
        with you. They will cut off your nose and ears, and any survivors will then
        be slaughtered by the sword. Your children will be taken away as captives,
        and everything that is left will be burned. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will strip you of your beautiful clothes and jewels. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In this way, I will put a stop to the lewdness and prostitution you
        brought from Egypt. You will never again cast longing eyes on those things
        or fondly remember your time in Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will surely hand you over to your enemies, to those you loathe, those
        you rejected. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will treat you with hatred and rob you of all you own, leaving
        you stark naked. The shame of your prostitution will be exposed to all the
        world. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You brought all this on yourself by prostituting yourself to other
        nations, defiling yourself with all their idols. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Because you have followed in your sister\u2019s footsteps, I will
        force you to drink the same cup of terror she drank.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says:\u201CYou will drink from your sister\u2019s cup of terror,a cup that
        is large and deep.It is filled to the brimwith scorn and derision.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Drunkenness and anguish will fill you,for your cup is filled to the
        brim with distress and desolation,the same cup your sister Samaria drank.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You will drain that cup of terrorto the very bottom.Then you will
        smash it to piecesand beat your breast in anguish.I, the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have spoken!  '
      comments: []
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Judgment on Both Sisters"
      content: "\u201CAnd because you have forgotten me and turned your back on me,
        this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: You must bear
        the consequences of all your lewdness and prostitution.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CSon of man, you
        must accuse Oholah and Oholibah of all their detestable sins. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They have committed both adultery and murder\u2014adultery by worshiping
        idols and murder by burning as sacrifices the children they bore to me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Furthermore, they have defiled my Temple and violated my Sabbath
        day! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the very day that they sacrificed their children to their idols,
        they boldly came into my Temple to worship! They came in and defiled my house.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou sisters sent messengers to distant lands to get men. Then
        when they arrived, you bathed yourselves, painted your eyelids, and put on
        your finest jewels for them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You sat with them on a beautifully embroidered couch and put my incense
        and my special oil on a table that was spread before you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From your room came the sound of many men carousing. They were lustful
        men and drunkards[[COMMENT(0)]] from the wilderness, who put bracelets on
        your wrists and beautiful crowns on your heads. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:42 '
        content: Or <b>Sabeans.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then I said, \u2018If they really want to have sex with old worn-out
        prostitutes like these, let them!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And that is what they did. They had sex with Oholah and Oholibah,
        these shameless prostitutes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But righteous people will judge these sister cities for what they
        really are\u2014adulterers and murderers.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Bring an army against them and hand them over to be terrorized and
        plundered. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For their enemies will stone them and kill them with swords. They
        will butcher their sons and daughters and burn their homes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In this way, I will put an end to lewdness and idolatry in the land,
        and my judgment will be a warning to all women not to follow your wicked
        example. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Sign of the Cooking Pot
      content: "  On January 15,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the ninth year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s
        captivity, this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments:
      - number: '24:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the tenth day of the tenth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on January 15, 588 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, write down today\u2019s date, because on this very
        day the king of Babylon is beginning his attack against Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then give these rebels an illustration with this message from the
        Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CPut a pot on the fire,and pour
        in some water.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Fill it with choice pieces of meat\u2014the rump and the shoulderand
        all the most tender cuts.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Use only the best sheep from the flock,and heap fuel on the fire
        beneath the pot.Bring the pot to a boil,and cook the bones along with the
        meat.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says:What sorrow awaits Jerusalem,the city of murderers!She is a cooking
        potwhose corruption can\u2019t be cleaned out.Take the meat out in random
        order,for no piece is better than another.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the blood of her murdersis splashed on the rocks.It isn\u2019t
        even spilled on the ground,where the dust could cover it!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I will splash her blood on a rockfor all to see,an expression
        of my angerand vengeance against her.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:What
        sorrow awaits Jerusalem,the city of murderers!I myself will pile up the fuel
        beneath her.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, heap on the wood!Let the fire roar to make the pot boil.Cook
        the meat with many spices,and afterward burn the bones.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now set the empty pot on the coals.Heat it red hot!Burn away the
        filth and corruption.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But it\u2019s hopeless;the corruption can\u2019t be cleaned out.So
        throw it into the fire.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your impurity is your lewdnessand the corruption of your idolatry.I
        tried to cleanse you,but you refused.So now you will remain in your filthuntil
        my fury against you has been satisfied.  '
      comments: []
    - title: "The Death of Ezekiel\u2019s Wife"
      content: "\u201CI, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken! The time has
        come, and I won\u2019t hold back. I will not change my mind, and I will have
        no pity on you. You will be judged on the basis of all your wicked actions,
        says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, with one blow I will take away your dearest treasure.
        Yet you must not show any sorrow at her death. Do not weep; let there be
        no tears. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Groan silently, but let there be no wailing at her grave. Do not
        uncover your head or take off your sandals. Do not perform the usual rituals
        of mourning or accept any food brought to you by consoling friends.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I proclaimed this to the people the next morning, and in the evening
        my wife died. The next morning I did everything I had been told to do. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the people asked, \u201CWhat does all this mean? What are you
        trying to tell us?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I said to them, \u201CA message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and I was told to give this message to the people of Israel. This
        is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: I will defile my
        Temple, the source of your security and pride, the place your heart delights
        in. Your sons and daughters whom you left behind in Judah will be slaughtered
        by the sword. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then you will do as Ezekiel has done. You will not mourn in public
        or console yourselves by eating the food brought by friends. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your heads will remain covered, and your sandals will not be taken
        off. You will not mourn or weep, but you will waste away because of your
        sins. You will groan among yourselves for all the evil you have done. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Ezekiel is an example for you; you will do just as he has done. And
        when that time comes, you will know that I am the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CSon of man,
        on the day I take away their stronghold\u2014their joy and glory, their heart\u2019s
        desire, their dearest treasure\u2014I will also take away their sons and
        daughters. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And on that day a survivor from Jerusalem will come to you in Babylon
        and tell you what has happened. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Message for Ammon
      content: '  Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn and face the land of Ammon and prophesy against
        its people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Give the Ammonites this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        Hear the word of the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! Because you cheered
        when my Temple was defiled, mocked Israel in her desolation, and laughed
        at Judah as she went away into exile, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will allow nomads from the eastern deserts to overrun your country.
        They will set up their camps among you and pitch their tents on your land.
        They will harvest all your fruit and drink the milk from your livestock. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will turn the city of Rabbah into a pasture for camels, and
        all the land of the Ammonites into a resting place for sheep and goats. Then
        you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        Because you clapped and danced and cheered with glee at the destruction of
        my people, "
      comments: []
    - title: A Message for Moab
      content: 'I will raise my fist of judgment against you. I will give you as
        plunder to many nations. I will cut you off from being a nation and destroy
        you completely. Then you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        Because the people of Moab[[COMMENT(0)]] have said that Judah is just like
        all the other nations, "
      comments:
      - number: '25:8 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>Moab and Seir.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "I will open up their eastern flank and wipe out their glorious frontier
        towns\u2014Beth-jeshimoth, Baal-meon, and Kiriathaim. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will hand Moab over to nomads from the eastern deserts, just
        as I handed over Ammon. Yes, the Ammonites will no longer be counted among
        the nations. '
      comments: []
    - title: A Message for Edom
      content: 'In the same way, I will bring my judgment down on the Moabites. Then
        they will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        The people of Edom have sinned greatly by avenging themselves against the
        people of Judah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, I will
        raise my fist of judgment against Edom. I will wipe out its people and animals
        with the sword. I will make a wasteland of everything from Teman to Dedan. '
      comments: []
    - title: A Message for Philistia
      content: 'I will accomplish this by the hand of my people of Israel. They will
        carry out my vengeance with anger, and Edom will know that this vengeance
        is from me. I, the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        The people of Philistia have acted against Judah out of bitter revenge and
        long-standing contempt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will raise my fist of judgment against the land of the Philistines.
        I will wipe out the Kerethites and utterly destroy the people who live by
        the sea. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Message for Tyre
      content: "  On February 3, during the twelfth year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s
        captivity,[[COMMENT(0)]] this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments:
      - number: '26:1 '
        content: 'Hebrew <b>In the eleventh year, on the first day of the month,
          </b>of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar year. Since an element is missing
          in the date formula here, scholars have reconstructed this probable reading:
          <b>In the eleventh [month of the twelfth] year, on the first day of the
          month. </b>This reading would put this message on February 3, 585 <span
          class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>; also see note on 1:1.'
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, Tyre has rejoiced over the fall of Jerusalem, saying,
        \u2018Ha! She who was the gateway to the rich trade routes to the east has
        been broken, and I am the heir! Because she has been made desolate, I will
        become wealthy!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I am your enemy, O Tyre, and I will bring many nations against you,
        like the waves of the sea crashing against your shoreline. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will destroy the walls of Tyre and tear down its towers. I will
        scrape away its soil and make it a bare rock! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It will be just a rock in the sea, a place for fishermen to spread
        their nets, for I have spoken, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Tyre will become the prey of many nations, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and its mainland villages will be destroyed by the sword. Then they
        will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        From the north I will bring King Nebuchadnezzar[[COMMENT(0)]] of Babylon
        against Tyre. He is king of kings and brings his horses, chariots, charioteers,
        and great army. "
      comments:
      - number: '26:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Nebuchadrezzar, </b>a variant spelling of Nebuchadnezzar.
    - title: 
      content: 'First he will destroy your mainland villages. Then he will attack
        you by building a siege wall, constructing a ramp, and raising a roof of
        shields against you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He will pound your walls with battering rams and demolish your towers
        with sledgehammers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The hooves of his horses will choke the city with dust, and the noise
        of the charioteers and chariot wheels will shake your walls as they storm
        through your broken gates. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'His horsemen will trample through every street in the city. They
        will butcher your people, and your strong pillars will topple.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThey will plunder all your riches and merchandise and break
        down your walls. They will destroy your lovely homes and dump your stones
        and timbers and even your dust into the sea. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will stop the music of your songs. No more will the sound of harps
        be heard among your people. '
      comments: []
    - title: "The Effect of Tyre\u2019s Destruction"
      content: 'I will make your island a bare rock, a place for fishermen to spread
        their nets. You will never be rebuilt, for I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have spoken. Yes, the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has spoken!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says
        to Tyre: The whole coastline will tremble at the sound of your fall, as the
        screams of the wounded echo in the continuing slaughter. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the seaport rulers will step down from their thrones and take
        off their royal robes and beautiful clothing. They will sit on the ground
        trembling with horror at your destruction. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they will wail for you, singing this funeral song:\u201CO famous
        island city,once ruler of the sea,how you have been destroyed!Your people,
        with their naval power,once spread fear around the world.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now the coastlands tremble at your fall.The islands are dismayed
        as you disappear.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        I will make Tyre an uninhabited ruin, like many others. I will bury you beneath
        the terrible waves of enemy attack. Great seas will swallow you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will send you to the pit to join those who descended there long
        ago. Your city will lie in ruins, buried beneath the earth, like those in
        the pit who have entered the world of the dead. You will have no place of
        respect here in the land of the living. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "The End of Tyre\u2019s Glory"
      content: '  Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, sing a funeral song for Tyre, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "that mighty gateway to the sea, the trading center of the world.
        Give Tyre this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CYou
        boasted, O Tyre,\u2018My beauty is perfect!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You extended your boundaries into the sea.Your builders made your
        beauty perfect.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You were like a great shipbuilt of the finest cypress from Senir.[[COMMENT(0)]]They
        took a cedar from Lebanonto make a mast for you.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:5 '
        content: Or <b>Hermon.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'They carved your oarsfrom the oaks of Bashan.Your deck of pine from
        the coasts of Cyprus[[COMMENT(0)]]was inlaid with ivory.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Kittim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Your sails were made of Egypt\u2019s finest linen,and they flew as
        a banner above you.You stood beneath blue and purple awningsmade bright with
        dyes from the coasts of Elishah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your oarsmen came from Sidon and Arvad;your helmsmen were skilled
        men from Tyre itself.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Wise old craftsmen from Gebal did the caulking.Ships from every land
        came with goods to barter for your trade.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMen from distant Persia, Lydia, and Libya[[COMMENT(0)]] served
        in your great army. They hung their shields and helmets on your walls, giving
        you great honor. "
      comments:
      - number: '27:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Paras, Lud, and Put.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Men from Arvad and Helech stood on your walls. Your towers were manned
        by men from Gammad. Their shields hung on your walls, completing your beauty.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTarshish sent merchants to buy your wares in exchange for silver,
        iron, tin, and lead. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Merchants from Greece,[[COMMENT(0)]] Tubal, and Meshech brought slaves
        and articles of bronze to trade with you.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Javan.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFrom Beth-togarmah came riding horses, chariot horses, and
        mules, all in exchange for your goods. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Merchants came to you from Dedan.[[COMMENT(0)]] Numerous coastlands
        were your captive markets; they brought payment in ivory tusks and ebony
        wood.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:15 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>Rhodes.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSyria[[COMMENT(0)]] sent merchants to buy your rich variety
        of goods. They traded turquoise, purple dyes, embroidery, fine linen, and
        jewelry of coral and rubies. "
      comments:
      - number: '27:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Aram; </b>some manuscripts read <b>Edom.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Judah and Israel traded for your wares, offering wheat from Minnith,
        figs,[[COMMENT(0)]] honey, olive oil, and balm.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:17 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDamascus sent merchants to buy your rich variety of goods,
        bringing wine from Helbon and white wool from Zahar. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Greeks from Uzal[[COMMENT(0)]] came to trade for your merchandise.
        Wrought iron, cassia, and fragrant calamus were bartered for your wares.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Vedan and Javan from Uzal. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew
          is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDedan sent merchants to trade their expensive saddle blankets
        with you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Arabians and the princes of Kedar sent merchants to trade lambs
        and rams and male goats in exchange for your goods. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The merchants of Sheba and Raamah came with all kinds of spices,
        jewels, and gold in exchange for your wares.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHaran, Canneh, Eden, Sheba, Asshur, and Kilmad came with their
        merchandise, too. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They brought choice fabrics to trade\u2014blue cloth, embroidery,
        and multicolored carpets rolled up and bound with cords. "
      comments: []
    - title: The Destruction of Tyre
      content: 'The ships of Tarshish were your ocean caravans. Your island warehouse
        was filled to the brim!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut look! Your oarsmenhave taken you into stormy seas!A mighty
        eastern galehas wrecked you in the heart of the sea!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Everything is lost\u2014your riches and wares,your sailors and pilots,your
        ship builders, merchants, and warriors.On the day of your ruin,everyone on
        board sinks into the depths of the sea.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your cities by the sea trembleas your pilots cry out in terror.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the oarsmen abandon their ships;the sailors and pilots stand
        on the shore.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They cry aloud over youand weep bitterly.They throw dust on their
        headsand roll in ashes.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They shave their heads in grief for youand dress themselves in burlap.They
        weep for you with bitter anguishand deep mourning.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As they wail and mourn over you,they sing this sad funeral song:\u2018Was
        there ever such a city as Tyre,now silent at the bottom of the sea?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The merchandise you tradedsatisfied the desires of many nations.Kings
        at the ends of the earthwere enriched by your trade.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now you are a wrecked ship,broken at the bottom of the sea.All your
        merchandise and crewhave gone down with you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All who live along the coastlandsare appalled at your terrible fate.Their
        kings are filled with horrorand look on with twisted faces.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "A Message for Tyre\u2019s King"
      content: '  Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give the prince of Tyre this message from the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CIn your great pride you claim, \u2018I
        am a god!I sit on a divine throne in the heart of the sea.\u2019But you are
        only a man and not a god,though you boast that you are a god.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You regard yourself as wiser than Danieland think no secret is hidden
        from you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "With your wisdom and understanding you have amassed great wealth\u2014gold
        and silver for your treasuries.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, your wisdom has made you very rich,and your riches have made
        you very proud.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says:Because you think you are as wise as a god,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will now bring against you a foreign army,the terror of the nations.They
        will draw their swords against your marvelous wisdomand defile your splendor!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will bring you down to the pit,and you will die in the heart
        of the sea,pierced with many wounds.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Will you then boast, \u2018I am a god!\u2019to those who kill you?To
        them you will be no godbut merely a man!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will die like an outcast[[COMMENT(0)]]at the hands of foreigners.I,
        the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '28:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>will die the death of the uncircumcised.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then this further message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, sing this funeral song for the king of Tyre. Give
        him this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CYou
        were the model of perfection,full of wisdom and exquisite in beauty.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You were in Eden,the garden of God.Your clothing was adorned with
        every precious stone[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014red carnelian, pale-green peridot,
        white moonstone,blue-green beryl, onyx, green jasper,blue lapis lazuli, turquoise,
        and emerald\u2014all beautifully crafted for youand set in the finest gold.They
        were given to youon the day you were created.  "
      comments:
      - number: '28:13 '
        content: The identification of some of these gemstones is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'I ordained and anointed youas the mighty angelic guardian.[[COMMENT(0)]]You
        had access to the holy mountain of Godand walked among the stones of fire.  '
      comments:
      - number: '28:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>guardian cherub; </b>similarly in 28:16.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou were blameless in all you didfrom the day you were createduntil
        the day evil was found in you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your rich commerce led you to violence,and you sinned.So I banished
        you in disgracefrom the mountain of God.I expelled you, O mighty guardian,from
        your place among the stones of fire.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your heart was filled with pridebecause of all your beauty.Your wisdom
        was corruptedby your love of splendor.So I threw you to the groundand exposed
        you to the curious gaze of kings.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You defiled your sanctuarieswith your many sins and your dishonest
        trade.So I brought fire out from within you,and it consumed you.I reduced
        you to ashes on the groundin the sight of all who were watching.  '
      comments: []
    - title: A Message for Sidon
      content: "All who knew you are appalled at your fate.You have come to a terrible
        end,and you will exist no more.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then another message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn and face the city of Sidon and prophesy against
        it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Give the people of Sidon this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CI
        am your enemy, O Sidon,and I will reveal my glory by what I do to you.When
        I bring judgment against youand reveal my holiness among you,everyone watching
        will knowthat I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will send a plague against you,and blood will be spilled in your
        streets.The attack will come from every direction,and your people will lie
        slaughtered within your walls.Then everyone will knowthat I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Restoration for Israel
      content: "No longer will Israel\u2019s scornful neighborsprick and tear at
        her like briers and thorns.For then they will knowthat I am the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        The people of Israel will again live in their own land, the land I gave my
        servant Jacob. For I will gather them from the distant lands where I have
        scattered them. I will reveal to the nations of the world my holiness among
        my people. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Message for Egypt
      content: "  On January 7,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the tenth year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s
        captivity, this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments:
      - number: '29:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the twelfth day of the tenth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on January 7, 587 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn and face Egypt and prophesy against Pharaoh
        the king and all the people of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Give them this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CI
        am your enemy, O Pharaoh, king of Egypt\u2014you great monster, lurking in
        the streams of the Nile.For you have said, \u2018The Nile River is mine;I
        made it for myself.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will put hooks in your jawsand drag you out on the landwith fish
        sticking to your scales.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will leave you and all your fishstranded in the wilderness to die.You
        will lie unburied on the open ground,for I have given you as food to the
        wild animals and birds.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the people of Egypt will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,for
        to Israel you were just a staff made of reeds.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Israel leaned on you,you splintered and brokeand stabbed her
        in the armpit.When she put her weight on you,you collapsed, and her legs
        gave way.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will bring an army against you, O Egypt, and destroy both people
        and animals. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The land of Egypt will become a desolate wasteland, and the Egyptians
        will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201CBecause you said,
        \u2018The Nile River is mine; I made it,\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I am now the enemy of both you and your river. I will make the land
        of Egypt a totally desolate wasteland, from Migdol to Aswan, as far south
        as the border of Ethiopia.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '29:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>from Migdol to Syene as far as the border of Cush.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'For forty years not a soul will pass that way, neither people nor
        animals. It will be completely uninhabited. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will make Egypt desolate, and it will be surrounded by other desolate
        nations. Its cities will be empty and desolate for forty years, surrounded
        by other ruined cities. I will scatter the Egyptians to distant lands.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        also says: At the end of the forty years I will bring the Egyptians home
        again from the nations to which they have been scattered. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will restore the prosperity of Egypt and bring its people back
        to the land of Pathros in southern Egypt from which they came. But Egypt
        will remain an unimportant, minor kingdom. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It will be the lowliest of all the nations, never again great enough
        to rise above its neighbors.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Nebuchadnezzar to Conquer Egypt
      content: "\u201CThen Israel will no longer be tempted to trust in Egypt for
        help. Egypt\u2019s shattered condition will remind Israel of how sinful she
        was to trust Egypt in earlier days. Then Israel will know that I am the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On April 26, the first day of the new year,[[COMMENT(0)]] during
        the twenty-seventh year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s captivity, this message
        came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments:
      - number: '29:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the first month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on April 26, 571 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, the army of King Nebuchadnezzar[[COMMENT(0)]] of
        Babylon fought so hard against Tyre that the warriors\u2019 heads were rubbed
        bare and their shoulders were raw and blistered. Yet Nebuchadnezzar and his
        army won no plunder to compensate them for all their work. "
      comments:
      - number: '29:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Nebuchadrezzar, </b>a variant spelling of Nebuchadnezzar;
          also in 29:19.
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will give the land of Egypt to Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon. He
        will carry off its wealth, plundering everything it has so he can pay his
        army. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, I have given him the land of Egypt as a reward for his work,
        says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, because he was working for
        me when he destroyed Tyre.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Sad Day for Egypt
      content: '  This is another message that came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy and give this message from the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CWeep and wailfor that day,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "for the terrible day is almost here\u2014the day of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!It
        is a day of clouds and gloom,a day of despair for the nations.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A sword will come against Egypt,and those who are slaughtered will
        cover the ground.Its wealth will be carried awayand its foundations destroyed.The
        land of Ethiopia[[COMMENT(0)]] will be ravished.  '
      comments:
      - number: '30:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Cush; </b>similarly in 30:9.
    - title: 
      content: 'Ethiopia, Libya, Lydia, all Arabia,[[COMMENT(0)]]and all their other
        allieswill be destroyed in that war.  '
      comments:
      - number: '30:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Cush, Put, Lud, all Arabia, Cub. </b><b>Cub </b>is otherwise
          unknown and may be another spelling for <b>Lub </b>(Libya).
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:All of
        Egypt\u2019s allies will fall,and the pride of her power will end.From Migdol
        to Aswan[[COMMENT(0)]]they will be slaughtered by the sword,says the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to Syene.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Egypt will be desolate,surrounded by desolate nations,and its cities
        will be in ruins,surrounded by other ruined cities.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the people of Egypt will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>when
        I have set Egypt on fireand destroyed all their allies.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At that time I will send swift messengers in shipsto terrify the
        complacent Ethiopians.Great panic will come upon themon that day of Egypt\u2019s
        certain destruction.Watch for it!It is sure to come!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says:By the power of King Nebuchadnezzar[[COMMENT(0)]] of Babylon,I will
        destroy the hordes of Egypt.  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Nebuchadrezzar, </b>a variant spelling of Nebuchadnezzar.
    - title: 
      content: "He and his armies\u2014the most ruthless of all\u2014will be sent
        to demolish the land.They will make war against Egyptuntil slaughtered Egyptians
        cover the ground.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will dry up the Nile Riverand sell the land to wicked men.I will
        destroy the land of Egypt and everything in itby the hands of foreigners.I,
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:I
        will smash the idols[[COMMENT(0)]] of Egyptand the images at Memphis.[[COMMENT(1)]]There
        will be no rulers left in Egypt;terror will sweep the land.  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:13a '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung.
      - number: '30:13b '
        content: Hebrew <b>Noph; </b>also in 30:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'I will destroy southern Egypt,[[COMMENT(0)]]set fire to Zoan,and
        bring judgment against Thebes.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '30:14a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Pathros.</b>
      - number: '30:14b '
        content: Hebrew <b>No; </b>also in 30:15, 16.
    - title: 
      content: 'I will pour out my fury on Pelusium,[[COMMENT(0)]]the strongest fortress
        of Egypt,and I will stamp outthe hordes of Thebes.  '
      comments:
      - number: '30:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Sin; </b>also in 30:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, I will set fire to all Egypt!Pelusium will be racked with pain;Thebes
        will be torn apart;Memphis will live in constant terror.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The young men of Heliopolis and Bubastis[[COMMENT(0)]] will die in
        battle,and the women[[COMMENT(1)]] will be taken away as slaves.  '
      comments:
      - number: '30:17a '
        content: Hebrew <b>of Awen and Pi-beseth.</b>
      - number: '30:17b '
        content: Or <b>and her cities.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'When I come to break the proud strength of Egypt,it will be a dark
        day for Tahpanhes, too.A dark cloud will cover Tahpanhes,and its daughters
        will be led away as captives.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Broken Arms of Pharaoh
      content: "And so I will greatly punish Egypt,and they will know that I am the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On April 29,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the eleventh year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s
        captivity, this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments:
      - number: '30:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the seventh day of the first month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on April 29, 587 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, I have broken the arm of Pharaoh, the king of Egypt.
        His arm has not been put in a cast so that it may heal. Neither has it been
        bound up with a splint to make it strong enough to hold a sword. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Therefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I am the enemy of Pharaoh, the king of Egypt! I will break both of
        his arms\u2014the good arm along with the broken one\u2014and I will make
        his sword clatter to the ground. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will scatter the Egyptians to many lands throughout the world. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will strengthen the arms of Babylon\u2019s king and put my sword
        in his hand. But I will break the arms of Pharaoh, king of Egypt, and he
        will lie there mortally wounded, groaning in pain. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will strengthen the arms of the king of Babylon, while the arms
        of Pharaoh fall useless to his sides. And when I put my sword in the hand
        of Babylon\u2019s king and he brings it against the land of Egypt, Egypt
        will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Egypt Compared to Fallen Assyria
      content: "  On June 21,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the eleventh year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s
        captivity, this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments:
      - number: '31:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the third month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on June 21, 587 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give this message to Pharaoh, king of Egypt, and
        all his hordes:\u201CTo whom would you compare your greatness?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You are like mighty Assyria,which was once like a cedar of Lebanon,with
        beautiful branches that cast deep forest shadeand with its top high among
        the clouds.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Deep springs watered itand helped it to grow tall and luxuriant.The
        water flowed around it like a river,streaming to all the trees nearby.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This great tree towered high,higher than all the other trees around
        it.It prospered and grew long thick branchesbecause of all the water at its
        roots.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The birds nested in its branches,and in its shade all the wild animals
        gave birth.All the great nations of the worldlived in its shadow.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It was strong and beautiful,with wide-spreading branches,for its
        roots went deepinto abundant water.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'No other cedar in the garden of Godcould rival it.No cypress had
        branches to equal it;no plane tree had boughs to compare.No tree in the garden
        of Godcame close to it in beauty.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Because I made this tree so beautiful,and gave it such magnificent
        foliage,it was the envy of all the other trees of Eden,the garden of God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Because Egypt[[COMMENT(0)]] became proud and arrogant, and because
        it set itself so high above the others, with its top reaching to the clouds, "
      comments:
      - number: '31:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>you.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'I will hand it over to a mighty nation that will destroy it as its
        wickedness deserves. I have already discarded it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A foreign army\u2014the terror of the nations\u2014has cut it down
        and left it fallen on the ground. Its branches are scattered across the mountains
        and valleys and ravines of the land. All those who lived in its shadow have
        gone away and left it lying there.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe birds roost on its fallen trunk,and the wild animals lie
        among its branches.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Let the tree of no other nationproudly exult in its own prosperity,though
        it be higher than the cloudsand it be watered from the depths.For all are
        doomed to die,to go down to the depths of the earth.They will land in the
        pitalong with everyone else on earth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        When Assyria went down to the grave,[[COMMENT(0)]] I made the deep springs
        mourn. I stopped its rivers and dried up its abundant water. I clothed Lebanon
        in black and caused the trees of the field to wilt. "
      comments:
      - number: '31:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to Sheol; </b>also in 31:16, 17.
    - title: 
      content: 'I made the nations shake with fear at the sound of its fall, for
        I sent it down to the grave with all the others who descend to the pit. And
        all the other proud trees of Eden, the most beautiful and the best of Lebanon,
        the ones whose roots went deep into the water, took comfort to find it there
        with them in the depths of the earth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Its allies, too, were all destroyed and had passed away. They had
        gone down to the grave\u2014all those nations that had lived in its shade.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Warning for Pharaoh
      content: "  On March 3,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the twelfth year of King Jehoiachin\u2019s
        captivity, this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments:
      - number: '32:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the twelfth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on March 3, 585 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, mourn for Pharaoh, king of Egypt, and give him
        this message:\u201CYou think of yourself as a strong young lion among the
        nations,but you are really just a sea monster,heaving around in your own
        rivers,stirring up mud with your feet.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says:I will send many peopleto catch you in my netand haul you out of the
        water.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will leave you stranded on the land to die.All the birds of the
        heavens will land on you,and the wild animals of the whole earthwill gorge
        themselves on you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will scatter your flesh on the hillsand fill the valleys with your
        bones.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will drench the earth with your gushing bloodall the way to the
        mountains,filling the ravines to the brim.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I blot you out,I will veil the heavens and darken the stars.I
        will cover the sun with a cloud,and the moon will not give you its light.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will darken the bright stars overheadand cover your land in darkness.I,
        the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have spoken!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI will disturb many hearts when I bring news of your downfall
        to distant nations you have never seen. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, I will shock many lands, and their kings will be terrified at
        your fate. They will shudder in fear for their lives as I brandish my sword
        before them on the day of your fall. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:\u201CThe
        sword of the king of Babylonwill come against you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will destroy your hordes with the swords of mighty warriors\u2014the
        terror of the nations.They will shatter the pride of Egypt,and all its hordes
        will be destroyed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will destroy all your flocks and herdsthat graze beside the streams.Never
        again will people or animalsmuddy those waters with their feet.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then I will let the waters of Egypt become calm again,and they will
        flow as smoothly as olive oil,says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And when I destroy Egyptand strip you of everything you ownand strike
        down all your people,then you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Egypt Falls into the Pit
      content: "Yes, this is the funeral songthey will sing for Egypt.Let all the
        nations mourn.Let them mourn for Egypt and its hordes.I, the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have spoken!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On March 17,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the twelfth year, another message
        came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments:
      - number: '32:17 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>On the fifteenth day of the month, </b>presumably in
          the twelfth month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar (see 32:1). This
          would put this message at the end of King Jehoiachin\u2019s twelfth year
          of captivity, on March 17, 585 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1. Greek version reads <b>On the fifteenth day of the
          first month, </b>which would put this message on April 27, 586 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>,
          at the beginning of Jehoiachin\u2019s twelfth year."
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, weep for the hordes of Egypt and for the other
        mighty nations.[[COMMENT(0)]] For I will send them down to the world below
        in company with those who descend to the pit. "
      comments:
      - number: '32:18 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "Say to them,\u2018O Egypt, are you lovelier than the other nations?No!
        So go down to the pit and lie there among the outcasts.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the uncircumcised; </b>also in 32:21, 24, 25, 26, 28,
          29, 30, 32.
    - title: 
      content: 'The Egyptians will fall with the many who have died by the sword,
        for the sword is drawn against them. Egypt and its hordes will be dragged
        away to their judgment. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Down in the grave[[COMMENT(0)]] mighty leaders will mockingly welcome
        Egypt and its allies, saying, \u2018They have come down; they lie among the
        outcasts, hordes slaughtered by the sword.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in Sheol.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAssyria lies there surrounded by the graves of its army, those
        who were slaughtered by the sword. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Their graves are in the depths of the pit, and they are surrounded
        by their allies. They struck terror in the hearts of people everywhere, but
        now they have been slaughtered by the sword.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CElam lies there surrounded by the graves of all its hordes,
        those who were slaughtered by the sword. They struck terror in the hearts
        of people everywhere, but now they have descended as outcasts to the world
        below. Now they lie in the pit and share the shame of those who have gone
        before them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They have a resting place among the slaughtered, surrounded by the
        graves of all their hordes. Yes, they terrorized the nations while they lived,
        but now they lie in shame with others in the pit, all of them outcasts, slaughtered
        by the sword.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMeshech and Tubal are there, surrounded by the graves of all
        their hordes. They once struck terror in the hearts of people everywhere.
        But now they are outcasts, all slaughtered by the sword. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They are not buried in honor like their fallen heroes, who went down
        to the grave[[COMMENT(0)]] with their weapons\u2014their shields covering
        their bodies[[COMMENT(1)]] and their swords beneath their heads. Their guilt
        rests upon them because they brought terror to everyone while they were still
        alive.  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:27a '
        content: Hebrew <b>to Sheol.</b>
      - number: '32:27b '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou too, Egypt, will lie crushed and broken among the outcasts,
        all slaughtered by the sword.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEdom is there with its kings and princes. Mighty as they were,
        they also lie among those slaughtered by the sword, with the outcasts who
        have gone down to the pit.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll the princes of the north and the Sidonians are there with
        others who have died. Once a terror, they have been put to shame. They lie
        there as outcasts with others who were slaughtered by the sword. They share
        the shame of all who have descended to the pit.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen Pharaoh and his entire army arrive, he will take comfort
        that he is not alone in having his hordes killed, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Ezekiel as Israel\u2019s Watchman"
      content: '  Once again a message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give your people this message: \u2018When I bring
        an army against a country, the people of that land choose one of their own
        to be a watchman. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the watchman sees the enemy coming, he sounds the alarm to warn
        the people. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then if those who hear the alarm refuse to take action, it is their
        own fault if they die. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They heard the alarm but ignored it, so the responsibility is theirs.
        If they had listened to the warning, they could have saved their lives. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if the watchman sees the enemy coming and doesn\u2019t sound
        the alarm to warn the people, he is responsible for their captivity. They
        will die in their sins, but I will hold the watchman responsible for their
        deaths.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow, son of man, I am making you a watchman for the people
        of Israel. Therefore, listen to what I say and warn them for me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If I announce that some wicked people are sure to die and you fail
        to tell them to change their ways, then they will die in their sins, and
        I will hold you responsible for their deaths. '
      comments: []
    - title: "The Watchman\u2019s Message"
      content: "But if you warn them to repent and they don\u2019t repent, they will
        die in their sins, but you will have saved yourself.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give the people of Israel this message: You are
        saying, \u2018Our sins are heavy upon us; we are wasting away! How can we
        survive?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        I take no pleasure in the death of wicked people. I only want them to turn
        from their wicked ways so they can live. Turn! Turn from your wickedness,
        O people of Israel! Why should you die?  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, give your people this message: The righteous behavior
        of righteous people will not save them if they turn to sin, nor will the
        wicked behavior of wicked people destroy them if they repent and turn from
        their sins. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I tell righteous people that they will live, but then they sin,
        expecting their past righteousness to save them, then none of their righteous
        acts will be remembered. I will destroy them for their sins. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And suppose I tell some wicked people that they will surely die,
        but then they turn from their sins and do what is just and right. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For instance, they might give back a debtor\u2019s security, return
        what they have stolen, and obey my life-giving laws, no longer doing what
        is evil. If they do this, then they will surely live and not die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'None of their past sins will be brought up again, for they have done
        what is just and right, and they will surely live.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYour people are saying, \u2018The Lord isn\u2019t doing what\u2019s
        right,\u2019 but it is they who are not doing what\u2019s right. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For again I say, when righteous people turn away from their righteous
        behavior and turn to evil, they will die. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if wicked people turn from their wickedness and do what is just
        and right, they will live. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Explanation of Jerusalem\u2019s Fall"
      content: "O people of Israel, you are saying, \u2018The Lord isn\u2019t doing
        what\u2019s right.\u2019 But I judge each of you according to your deeds.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On January 8,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the twelfth year of our captivity,
        a survivor from Jerusalem came to me and said, \u201CThe city has fallen!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '33:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the fifth day of the tenth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on January 8, 585 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: 'The previous evening the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had taken hold
        of me and given me back my voice. So I was able to speak when this man arrived
        the next morning.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, the scattered remnants of Israel living among the
        ruined cities keep saying, \u2018Abraham was only one man, yet he gained
        possession of the entire land. We are many; surely the land has been given
        to us as a possession.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So tell these people, \u2018This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: You eat meat with blood in it, you worship idols,[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        you murder the innocent. Do you really think the land should be yours? "
      comments:
      - number: '33:25 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung.
    - title: 
      content: "Murderers! Idolaters! Adulterers! Should the land belong to you?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSay to them, \u2018This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: As surely as I live, those living in the ruins will die by the sword.
        And I will send wild animals to eat those living in the open fields. Those
        hiding in the forts and caves will die of disease. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will completely destroy the land and demolish her pride. Her arrogant
        power will come to an end. The mountains of Israel will be so desolate that
        no one will even travel through them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When I have completely destroyed the land because of their detestable
        sins, then they will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, your people talk about you in their houses and
        whisper about you at the doors. They say to each other, \u2018Come on, let\u2019s
        go hear the prophet tell us what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is saying!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So my people come pretending to be sincere and sit before you. They
        listen to your words, but they have no intention of doing what you say. Their
        mouths are full of lustful words, and their hearts seek only after money. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You are very entertaining to them, like someone who sings love songs
        with a beautiful voice or plays fine music on an instrument. They hear what
        you say, but they don\u2019t act on it! "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Shepherds of Israel
      content: '  Then this message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, prophesy against the shepherds, the leaders of
        Israel. Give them this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        What sorrow awaits you shepherds who feed yourselves instead of your flocks.
        Shouldn\u2019t shepherds feed their sheep? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You drink the milk, wear the wool, and butcher the best animals,
        but you let your flocks starve. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have not taken care of the weak. You have not tended the sick
        or bound up the injured. You have not gone looking for those who have wandered
        away and are lost. Instead, you have ruled them with harshness and cruelty. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So my sheep have been scattered without a shepherd, and they are
        easy prey for any wild animal. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They have wandered through all the mountains and all the hills, across
        the face of the earth, yet no one has gone to search for them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, you shepherds, hear the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        you abandoned my flock and left them to be attacked by every wild animal.
        And though you were my shepherds, you didn\u2019t search for my sheep when
        they were lost. You took care of yourselves and left the sheep to starve. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, you shepherds, hear the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Good Shepherd
      content: 'This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: I now
        consider these shepherds my enemies, and I will hold them responsible for
        what has happened to my flock. I will take away their right to feed the flock,
        and I will stop them from feeding themselves. I will rescue my flock from
        their mouths; the sheep will no longer be their prey.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I myself will search and find my sheep. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will be like a shepherd looking for his scattered flock. I will
        find my sheep and rescue them from all the places where they were scattered
        on that dark and cloudy day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will bring them back home to their own land of Israel from among
        the peoples and nations. I will feed them on the mountains of Israel and
        by the rivers and in all the places where people live. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, I will give them good pastureland on the high hills of Israel.
        There they will lie down in pleasant places and feed in the lush pastures
        of the hills. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I myself will tend my sheep and give them a place to lie down in
        peace, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will search for my lost ones who strayed away, and I will bring
        them safely home again. I will bandage the injured and strengthen the weak.
        But I will destroy those who are fat and powerful. I will feed them, yes\u2014feed
        them justice!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd as for you, my flock, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says to his people: I will judge between one animal of the flock and another,
        separating the sheep from the goats. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isn\u2019t it enough for you to keep the best of the pastures for
        yourselves? Must you also trample down the rest? Isn\u2019t it enough for
        you to drink clear water for yourselves? Must you also muddy the rest with
        your feet? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Why must my flock eat what you have trampled down and drink water
        you have fouled?  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will surely judge between the fat sheep and the scrawny sheep. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For you fat sheep pushed and butted and crowded my sick and hungry
        flock until you scattered them to distant lands. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I will rescue my flock, and they will no longer be abused. I will
        judge between one animal of the flock and another. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will set over them one shepherd, my servant David. He will
        feed them and be a shepherd to them. '
      comments: []
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant of Peace"
      content: 'And I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, will be their God, and my
        servant David will be a prince among my people. I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have spoken!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI will make a covenant of peace with my people and drive away
        the dangerous animals from the land. Then they will be able to camp safely
        in the wildest places and sleep in the woods without fear. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will bless my people and their homes around my holy hill. And in
        the proper season I will send the showers they need. There will be showers
        of blessing. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The orchards and fields of my people will yield bumper crops, and
        everyone will live in safety. When I have broken their chains of slavery
        and rescued them from those who enslaved them, then they will know that I
        am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will no longer be prey for other nations, and wild animals will
        no longer devour them. They will live in safety, and no one will frighten
        them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd I will make their land famous for its crops, so my people
        will never again suffer from famines or the insults of foreign nations. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In this way, they will know that I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        their God, am with them. And they will know that they, the people of Israel,
        are my people, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Message for Edom
      content: '  Again a message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn and face Mount Seir, and prophesy against
        its people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Give them this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CI
        am your enemy, O Mount Seir,and I will raise my fist against youto destroy
        you completely.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will demolish your citiesand make you desolate.Then you will know
        that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYour eternal hatred for the people of Israel led you to butcher
        them when they were helpless, when I had already punished them for all their
        sins. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        since you show no distaste for blood, I will give you a bloodbath of your
        own. Your turn has come! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will make Mount Seir utterly desolate, killing off all who try
        to escape and any who return. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will fill your mountains with the dead. Your hills, your valleys,
        and your ravines will be filled with people slaughtered by the sword. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will make you desolate forever. Your cities will never be rebuilt.
        Then you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor you said, \u2018The lands of Israel and Judah will be ours.
        We will take possession of them. What do we care that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is there!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, as surely as I live, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        I will pay back your angry deeds with my own. I will punish you for all your
        acts of anger, envy, and hatred. And I will make myself known to Israel[[COMMENT(0)]]
        by what I do to you. '
      comments:
      - number: '35:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to them; </b>Greek version reads <b>to you.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then you will know that I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have
        heard every contemptuous word you spoke against the mountains of Israel.
        For you said, \u2018They are desolate; they have been given to us as food
        to eat!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In saying that, you boasted proudly against me, and I have heard
        it all!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        The whole world will rejoice when I make you desolate. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Restoration for Israel
      content: "  \u201CSon of man, prophesy to Israel\u2019s mountains. Give them
        this message: O mountains of Israel, hear the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Your
        enemies have taunted you, saying, \u2018Aha! Now the ancient heights belong
        to us!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, son of man, give the mountains of Israel this message
        from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: Your enemies have attacked
        you from all directions, making you the property of many nations and the
        object of much mocking and slander. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, O mountains of Israel, hear the word of the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. He speaks to the hills and mountains, ravines
        and valleys, and to ruined wastes and long-deserted cities that have been
        destroyed and mocked by the surrounding nations. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: My jealous
        anger burns against these nations, especially Edom, because they have shown
        utter contempt for me by gleefully taking my land for themselves as plunder.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, prophesy to the hills and mountains, the ravines
        and valleys of Israel. This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I am furious that you have suffered shame before the surrounding nations. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I have taken a solemn oath that those nations will soon have their
        own shame to endure.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut the mountains of Israel will produce heavy crops of fruit
        for my people\u2014for they will be coming home again soon! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'See, I care about you, and I will pay attention to you. Your ground
        will be plowed and your crops planted. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will greatly increase the population of Israel, and the ruined
        cities will be rebuilt and filled with people. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will increase not only the people, but also your animals. O mountains
        of Israel, I will bring people to live on you once again. I will make you
        even more prosperous than you were before. Then you will know that I am the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will cause my people to walk on you once again, and you will be
        their territory. You will never again rob them of their children.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        The other nations taunt you, saying, \u2018Israel is a land that devours
        its own people and robs them of their children!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But you will never again devour your people or rob them of their
        children, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will not let you hear those other nations insult you, and you will
        no longer be mocked by them. You will not be a land that causes its nation
        to fall, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then this further message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, when the people of Israel were living in their
        own land, they defiled it by the evil way they lived. To me their conduct
        was as unclean as a woman\u2019s menstrual cloth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They polluted the land with murder and the worship of idols,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        so I poured out my fury on them. '
      comments:
      - number: '36:18 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung; also in 36:25.
    - title: 
      content: 'I scattered them to many lands to punish them for the evil way they
        had lived. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when they were scattered among the nations, they brought shame
        on my holy name. For the nations said, \u2018These are the people of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, but he couldn\u2019t keep them safe in his own
        land!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then I was concerned for my holy name, on which my people brought
        shame among the nations.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, give the people of Israel this message from the
        Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: I am bringing you back, but not because
        you deserve it. I am doing it to protect my holy name, on which you brought
        shame while you were scattered among the nations. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will show how holy my great name is\u2014the name on which you
        brought shame among the nations. And when I reveal my holiness through you
        before their very eyes, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, then
        the nations will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For I will gather you up from all the nations and bring you home
        again to your land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen I will sprinkle clean water on you, and you will be clean.
        Your filth will be washed away, and you will no longer worship idols. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will give you a new heart, and I will put a new spirit in you.
        I will take out your stony, stubborn heart and give you a tender, responsive
        heart.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a heart of flesh.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will put my Spirit in you so that you will follow my decrees
        and be careful to obey my regulations.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd you will live in Israel, the land I gave your ancestors
        long ago. You will be my people, and I will be your God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will cleanse you of your filthy behavior. I will give you good
        crops of grain, and I will send no more famines on the land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will give you great harvests from your fruit trees and fields,
        and never again will the surrounding nations be able to scoff at your land
        for its famines. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then you will remember your past sins and despise yourselves for
        all the detestable things you did. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But remember, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, I am
        not doing this because you deserve it. O my people of Israel, you should
        be utterly ashamed of all you have done!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        When I cleanse you from your sins, I will repopulate your cities, and the
        ruins will be rebuilt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fields that used to lie empty and desolate in plain view of everyone
        will again be farmed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And when I bring you back, people will say, \u2018This former wasteland
        is now like the Garden of Eden! The abandoned and ruined cities now have
        strong walls and are filled with people!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the surrounding nations that survive will know that I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have rebuilt the ruins and replanted the wasteland. For I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have spoken, and I will do what I say.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        I am ready to hear Israel\u2019s prayers and to increase their numbers like
        a flock. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Valley of Dry Bones
      content: '  The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> took hold of me, and I was carried
        away by the Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to a valley filled
        with bones. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He led me all around among the bones that covered the valley floor.
        They were scattered everywhere across the ground and were completely dried
        out. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he asked me, \u201CSon of man, can these bones become living
        people again?\u201D\u201CO Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,\u201D I
        replied, \u201Cyou alone know the answer to that.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CSpeak a prophetic message to these bones
        and say, \u2018Dry bones, listen to the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Look!
        I am going to put breath into you and make you live again! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will put flesh and muscles on you and cover you with skin. I will
        put breath into you, and you will come to life. Then you will know that I
        am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I spoke this message, just as he told me. Suddenly as I spoke,
        there was a rattling noise all across the valley. The bones of each body
        came together and attached themselves as complete skeletons. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then as I watched, muscles and flesh formed over the bones. Then
        skin formed to cover their bodies, but they still had no breath in them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CSpeak a prophetic message to the winds,
        son of man. Speak a prophetic message and say, \u2018This is what the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Come, O breath, from the four winds! Breathe
        into these dead bodies so they may live again.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I spoke the message as he commanded me, and breath came into their
        bodies. They all came to life and stood up on their feet\u2014a great army.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CSon of man, these bones represent the people
        of Israel. They are saying, \u2018We have become old, dry bones\u2014all
        hope is gone. Our nation is finished.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Therefore, prophesy to them and say, \u2018This is what the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: O my people, I will open your graves of
        exile and cause you to rise again. Then I will bring you back to the land
        of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When this happens, O my people, you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: Reunion of Israel and Judah
      content: "I will put my Spirit in you, and you will live again and return home
        to your own land. Then you will know that I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        have spoken, and I have done what I said. Yes, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has spoken!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Again a message came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, take a piece of wood and carve on it these words:
        \u2018This represents Judah and its allied tribes.\u2019 Then take another
        piece and carve these words on it: \u2018This represents Ephraim and the
        northern tribes of Israel.\u2019[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '37:16 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>This is Ephraim\u2019s wood, representing Joseph and
          all the house of Israel; </b>similarly in 37:19."
    - title: 
      content: 'Now hold them together in your hand as if they were one piece of
        wood. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When your people ask you what your actions mean, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "say to them, \u2018This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will take Ephraim and the northern tribes and join them to Judah.
        I will make them one piece of wood in my hand.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen hold out the pieces of wood you have inscribed, so the
        people can see them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And give them this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        I will gather the people of Israel from among the nations. I will bring them
        home to their own land from the places where they have been scattered. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will unify them into one nation on the mountains of Israel. One
        king will rule them all; no longer will they be divided into two nations
        or into two kingdoms. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will never again pollute themselves with their idols[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and vile images and rebellion, for I will save them from their sinful apostasy.[[COMMENT(1)]]
        I will cleanse them. Then they will truly be my people, and I will be their
        God.  '
      comments:
      - number: '37:23a '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung.
      - number: '37:23b '
        content: As in many Hebrew manuscripts and Greek version; Masoretic Text
          reads <b>from all their dwelling places where they sinned.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMy servant David will be their king, and they will have only
        one shepherd. They will obey my regulations and be careful to keep my decrees. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will live in the land I gave my servant Jacob, the land where
        their ancestors lived. They and their children and their grandchildren after
        them will live there forever, generation after generation. And my servant
        David will be their prince forever. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will make a covenant of peace with them, an everlasting covenant.
        I will give them their land and increase their numbers,[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        I will put my Temple among them forever. '
      comments:
      - number: '37:26 '
        content: Hebrew reads <b>I will give them and increase their numbers; </b>Greek
          version lacks the entire phrase.
    - title: 
      content: 'I will make my home among them. I will be their God, and they will
        be my people. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Message for Gog
      content: '  This is another message that came to me from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, turn and face Gog of the land of Magog, the prince
        who rules over the nations of Meshech and Tubal, and prophesy against him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Give him this message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        Gog, I am your enemy! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will turn you around and put hooks in your jaws to lead you out
        with your whole army\u2014your horses and charioteers in full armor and a
        great horde armed with shields and swords. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Persia, Ethiopia, and Libya[[COMMENT(0)]] will join you, too, with
        all their weapons. '
      comments:
      - number: '38:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Paras, Cush, and Put.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Gomer and all its armies will also join you, along with the armies
        of Beth-togarmah from the distant north, and many others.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGet ready; be prepared! Keep all the armies around you mobilized,
        and take command of them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A long time from now you will be called into action. In the distant
        future you will swoop down on the land of Israel, which will be enjoying
        peace after recovering from war and after its people have returned from many
        lands to the mountains of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You and all your allies\u2014a vast and awesome army\u2014will roll
        down on them like a storm and cover the land like a cloud.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        At that time evil thoughts will come to your mind, and you will devise a
        wicked scheme. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will say, \u2018Israel is an unprotected land filled with unwalled
        villages! I will march against her and destroy these people who live in such
        confidence! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will go to those formerly desolate cities that are now filled with
        people who have returned from exile in many nations. I will capture vast
        amounts of plunder, for the people are rich with livestock and other possessions
        now. They think the whole world revolves around them!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Sheba and Dedan and the merchants of Tarshish will ask, \u2018Do
        you really think the armies you have gathered can rob them of silver and
        gold? Do you think you can drive away their livestock and seize their goods
        and carry off plunder?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, son of man, prophesy against Gog. Give him this
        message from the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: When my people are
        living in peace in their land, then you will rouse yourself.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '38:14 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>then you will know.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'You will come from your homeland in the distant north with your vast
        cavalry and your mighty army, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and you will attack my people Israel, covering their land like a
        cloud. At that time in the distant future, I will bring you against my land
        as everyone watches, and my holiness will be displayed by what happens to
        you, Gog. Then all the nations will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asks:
        Are you the one I was talking about long ago, when I announced through Israel\u2019s
        prophets that in the future I would bring you against my people? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        When Gog invades the land of Israel, my fury will boil over! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In my jealousy and blazing anger, I promise a mighty shaking in the
        land of Israel on that day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All living things\u2014the fish in the sea, the birds of the sky,
        the animals of the field, the small animals that scurry along the ground,
        and all the people on earth\u2014will quake in terror at my presence. Mountains
        will be thrown down; cliffs will crumble; walls will fall to the earth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will summon the sword against you on all the hills of Israel, says
        the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Your men will turn their swords
        against each other. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will punish you and your armies with disease and bloodshed; I will
        send torrential rain, hailstones, fire, and burning sulfur! '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "The Slaughter of Gog\u2019s Hordes"
      content: "  \u201CSon of man, prophesy against Gog. Give him this message from
        the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: I am your enemy, O Gog, ruler
        of the nations of Meshech and Tubal. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will turn you around and drive you toward the mountains of Israel,
        bringing you from the distant north. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will knock the bow from your left hand and the arrows from your
        right hand, and I will leave you helpless. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You and your army and your allies will all die on the mountains.
        I will feed you to the vultures and wild animals. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You will fall in the open fields, for I have spoken, says the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will rain down fire on Magog and on all your allies who live
        safely on the coasts. Then they will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn this way, I will make known my holy name among my people
        of Israel. I will not let anyone bring shame on it. And the nations, too,
        will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the Holy One of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That day of judgment will come, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Everything will happen just as I have declared it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen the people in the towns of Israel will go out and pick
        up your small and large shields, bows and arrows, javelins and spears, and
        they will use them for fuel. There will be enough to last them seven years! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They won\u2019t need to cut wood from the fields or forests, for
        these weapons will give them all the fuel they need. They will plunder those
        who planned to plunder them, and they will rob those who planned to rob them,
        says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd I will make a vast graveyard for Gog and his hordes in
        the Valley of the Travelers, east of the Dead Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]] It will
        block the way of those who travel there, and they will change the name of
        the place to the Valley of Gog\u2019s Hordes. "
      comments:
      - number: '39:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'It will take seven months for the people of Israel to bury the bodies
        and cleanse the land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Everyone in Israel will help, for it will be a glorious victory for
        Israel when I demonstrate my glory on that day, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAfter seven months, teams of men will be appointed to search
        the land for skeletons to bury, so the land will be made clean again. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Whenever bones are found, a marker will be set up so the burial crews
        will take them to be buried in the Valley of Gog\u2019s Hordes. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "(There will be a town there named Hamonah, which means \u2018horde.\u2019)
        And so the land will finally be cleansed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd now, son of man, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Call all the birds and wild animals. Say to them: Gather together for
        my great sacrificial feast. Come from far and near to the mountains of Israel,
        and there eat flesh and drink blood! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Eat the flesh of mighty men and drink the blood of princes as though
        they were rams, lambs, goats, and bulls\u2014all fattened animals from Bashan! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Gorge yourselves with flesh until you are glutted; drink blood until
        you are drunk. This is the sacrificial feast I have prepared for you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Feast at my banquet table\u2014feast on horses and charioteers, on
        mighty men and all kinds of valiant warriors, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn this way, I will demonstrate my glory to the nations. Everyone
        will see the punishment I have inflicted on them and the power of my fist
        when I strike. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And from that time on the people of Israel will know that I am the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The nations will then know why Israel was sent away to exile\u2014it
        was punishment for sin, for they were unfaithful to their God. Therefore,
        I turned away from them and let their enemies destroy them. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Restoration for God\u2019s People"
      content: 'I turned my face away and punished them because of their defilement
        and their sins.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo now, this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I will end the captivity of my people[[COMMENT(0)]]; I will have mercy
        on all Israel, for I jealously guard my holy reputation! "
      comments:
      - number: '39:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>of Jacob.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'They will accept responsibility for[[COMMENT(0)]] their past shame
        and unfaithfulness after they come home to live in peace in their own land,
        with no one to bother them. '
      comments:
      - number: '39:26 '
        content: A few Hebrew manuscripts read <b>They will forget.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'When I bring them home from the lands of their enemies, I will display
        my holiness among them for all the nations to see. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then my people will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        their God, because I sent them away to exile and brought them home again.
        I will leave none of my people behind. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The New Temple Area
      content: "  On April 28,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the twenty-fifth year of our
        captivity\u2014fourteen years after the fall of Jerusalem\u2014the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        took hold of me. "
      comments:
      - number: '40:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>At the beginning of the year, on the tenth day of the
          month, </b>of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. This event occurred on
          April 28, 573 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>; also
          see note on 1:1.
    - title: 
      content: 'In a vision from God he took me to the land of Israel and set me
        down on a very high mountain. From there I could see toward the south what
        appeared to be a city. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As he brought me nearer, I saw a man whose face shone like bronze
        standing beside a gateway entrance. He was holding in his hand a linen measuring
        cord and a measuring rod.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The East Gateway
      content: "He said to me, \u201CSon of man, watch and listen. Pay close attention
        to everything I show you. You have been brought here so I can show you many
        things. Then you will return to the people of Israel and tell them everything
        you have seen.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I could see a wall completely surrounding the Temple area. The man
        took a measuring rod that was 10-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] long and measured
        the wall, and the wall was 10-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] thick and 10-1/2 feet
        high.  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:5a '
        content: Hebrew <b>6 long cubits </b>[3.2 meters], <b>each being a cubit
          </b>[18 inches or 45 centimeters] <b>and a handbreadth </b>[3 inches or
          8 centimeters] <b>in length.</b>
      - number: '40:5b '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 rod </b>[3.2 meters]; also in 40:5c, 7.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he went over to the eastern gateway. He climbed the steps and
        measured the threshold of the gateway; it was 10-1/2 feet front to back.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:6 '
        content: As in Greek version, which reads <b>1 rod </b>[3.2 meters] <b>deep;
          </b>Hebrew reads <b>1 rod deep, and 1 threshold, 1 rod deep.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "There were guard alcoves on each side built into the gateway passage.
        Each of these alcoves was 10-1/2 feet square, with a distance between them
        of 8-3/4 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] along the passage wall. The gateway\u2019s inner
        threshold, which led to the entry room at the inner end of the gateway passage,
        was 10-1/2 feet front to back. "
      comments:
      - number: '40:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.7 meters]; also in 40:48.
    - title: 
      content: 'He also measured the entry room of the gateway.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:8 '
        content: As in many Hebrew manuscripts and Syriac version; other Hebrew manuscripts
          add <b>which faced inward toward the Temple; it was 1 rod </b>[10.5 feet
          or 3.2 meters] <b>deep. </b><b>Then he measured the entry room of the gateway.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'It was 14 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] across, with supporting columns 3-1/2
        feet[[COMMENT(1)]] thick. This entry room was at the inner end of the gateway
        structure, facing toward the Temple.  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:9a '
        content: Hebrew <b>8 cubits </b>[4.2 meters].
      - number: '40:9b '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 cubits </b>[1.1 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'There were three guard alcoves on each side of the gateway passage.
        Each had the same measurements, and the dividing walls separating them were
        also identical. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The man measured the gateway entrance, which was 17-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide at the opening and 22-3/4 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] wide in the gateway passage. '
      comments:
      - number: '40:11a '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[5.3 meters].
      - number: '40:11b '
        content: Hebrew <b>13 cubits </b>[6.9 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'In front of each of the guard alcoves was a 21-inch[[COMMENT(0)]]
        curb. The alcoves themselves were 10-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] on each side.  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:12a '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 cubit </b>[53 centimeters].
      - number: '40:12b '
        content: Hebrew <b>6 cubits </b>[3.2 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he measured the entire width of the gateway, measuring the distance
        between the back walls of facing guard alcoves; this distance was 43-3/4
        feet.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>25 cubits </b>[13.3 meters]; also in 40:21, 25, 29, 30,
          33, 36.
    - title: 
      content: 'He measured the dividing walls all along the inside of the gateway
        up to the entry room of the gateway; this distance was 105 feet.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>60 cubits </b>[31.8 meters]. Greek version reads <b>20
          cubits </b>[35 feet or 10.6 meters]. The meaning of the Hebrew in this
          verse is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'The full length of the gateway passage was 87-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        from one end to the other. '
      comments:
      - number: '40:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 cubits </b>[26.5 meters]; also in 40:21, 25, 29, 33,
          36.
    - title: The Outer Courtyard
      content: 'There were recessed windows that narrowed inward through the walls
        of the guard alcoves and their dividing walls. There were also windows in
        the entry room. The surfaces of the dividing walls were decorated with carved
        palm trees.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the man brought me through the gateway into the outer courtyard
        of the Temple. A stone pavement ran along the walls of the courtyard, and
        thirty rooms were built against the walls, opening onto the pavement. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This pavement flanked the gates and extended out from the walls into
        the courtyard the same distance as the gateway entrance. This was the lower
        pavement. '
      comments: []
    - title: The North Gateway
      content: "Then the man measured across the Temple\u2019s outer courtyard between
        the outer and inner gateways; the distance was 175 feet.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '40:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 cubits </b>[53 meters]; also in 40:23, 27, 47.
    - title: 
      content: 'The man measured the gateway on the north just like the one on the
        east. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Here, too, there were three guard alcoves on each side, with dividing
        walls and an entry room. All the measurements matched those of the east gateway.
        The gateway passage was 87-1/2 feet long and 43-3/4 feet wide between the
        back walls of facing guard alcoves. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The windows, the entry room, and the palm tree decorations were identical
        to those in the east gateway. There were seven steps leading up to the gateway
        entrance, and the entry room was at the inner end of the gateway passage. '
      comments: []
    - title: The South Gateway
      content: "Here on the north side, just as on the east, there was another gateway
        leading to the Temple\u2019s inner courtyard directly opposite this outer
        gateway. The distance between the two gateways was 175 feet.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the man took me around to the south gateway and measured its
        various parts, and they were exactly the same as in the others. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It had windows along the walls as the others did, and there was an
        entry room where the gateway passage opened into the outer courtyard. And
        like the others, the gateway passage was 87-1/2 feet long and 43-3/4 feet
        wide between the back walls of facing guard alcoves. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This gateway also had a stairway of seven steps leading up to it,
        and an entry room at the inner end, and palm tree decorations along the dividing
        walls. '
      comments: []
    - title: Gateways to the Inner Courtyard
      content: 'And here again, directly opposite the outer gateway, was another
        gateway that led into the inner courtyard. The distance between the two gateways
        was 175 feet.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the man took me to the south gateway leading into the inner
        courtyard. He measured it, and it had the same measurements as the other
        gateways. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Its guard alcoves, dividing walls, and entry room were the same size
        as those in the others. It also had windows along its walls and in the entry
        room. And like the others, the gateway passage was 87-1/2 feet long and 43-3/4
        feet wide. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(The entry rooms of the gateways leading into the inner courtyard
        were 14 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] across and 43-3/4 feet wide.) '
      comments:
      - number: '40:30 '
        content: As in 40:9, which reads <b>8 cubits </b>[14 feet or 4.2 meters];
          here the Hebrew reads <b>5 cubits </b>[8-3/4 feet or 2.7 meters]. Some
          Hebrew manuscripts and the Greek version lack this entire verse.
    - title: 
      content: 'The entry room to the south gateway faced into the outer courtyard.
        It had palm tree decorations on its columns, and there were eight steps leading
        to its entrance.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he took me to the east gateway leading to the inner courtyard.
        He measured it, and it had the same measurements as the other gateways. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Its guard alcoves, dividing walls, and entry room were the same size
        as those of the others, and there were windows along the walls and in the
        entry room. The gateway passage measured 87-1/2 feet long and 43-3/4 feet
        wide. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Its entry room faced into the outer courtyard. It had palm tree decorations
        on its columns, and there were eight steps leading to its entrance.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he took me around to the north gateway leading to the inner
        courtyard. He measured it, and it had the same measurements as the other
        gateways. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The guard alcoves, dividing walls, and entry room of this gateway
        had the same measurements as in the others and the same window arrangements.
        The gateway passage measured 87-1/2 feet long and 43-3/4 feet wide. '
      comments: []
    - title: Rooms for Preparing Sacrifices
      content: 'Its entry room[[COMMENT(0)]] faced into the outer courtyard, and
        it had palm tree decorations on the columns. There were eight steps leading
        to its entrance.  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:37 '
        content: As in Greek version (compare parallels at 40:26, 31, 34); Hebrew
          reads <b>Its dividing wall.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'A door led from the entry room of one of the inner gateways into
        a side room, where the meat for sacrifices was washed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On each side of this entry room were two tables, where the sacrificial
        animals were slaughtered for the burnt offerings, sin offerings, and guilt
        offerings. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Outside the entry room, on each side of the stairs going up to the
        north entrance, were two more tables. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So there were eight tables in all\u2014four inside and four outside\u2014where
        the sacrifices were cut up and prepared. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There were also four tables of finished stone for preparation of
        the burnt offerings, each 31-1/2 inches square and 21 inches high.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        On these tables were placed the butchering knives and other implements for
        slaughtering the sacrificial animals. '
      comments:
      - number: '40:42 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1-1/2 cubits </b>[80 centimeters] <b>long and 1-1/2 cubits
          wide and 1 cubit </b>[53 centimeters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: Rooms for the Priests
      content: 'There were hooks, each 3 inches[[COMMENT(0)]] long, fastened all
        around the foyer walls. The sacrificial meat was laid on the tables.  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:43 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a handbreadth </b>[8 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Inside the inner courtyard were two rooms,[[COMMENT(0)]] one beside
        the north gateway, facing south, and the other beside the south[[COMMENT(1)]]
        gateway, facing north. '
      comments:
      - number: '40:44a '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>rooms for singers.</b>
      - number: '40:44b '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>east.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "And the man said to me, \u201CThe room beside the north inner gate
        is for the priests who supervise the Temple maintenance. "
      comments: []
    - title: The Inner Courtyard and Temple
      content: "The room beside the south inner gate is for the priests in charge
        of the altar\u2014the descendants of Zadok\u2014for they alone of all the
        Levites may approach the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to minister to him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the man measured the inner courtyard, and it was a square, 175
        feet wide and 175 feet across. The altar stood in the courtyard in front
        of the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he brought me to the entry room of the Temple. He measured the
        walls on either side of the opening to the entry room, and they were 8-3/4
        feet thick. The entrance itself was 24-1/2 feet wide, and the walls on each
        side of the entrance were an additional 5-1/4 feet long.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '40:48 '
        content: As in Greek version, which reads <b>The entrance was 14 cubits </b>[7.4
          meters] <b>wide, and the walls of the entrance were 3 cubits </b>[1.6 meters]
          <b>on each side; </b>Hebrew lacks <b>14 cubits wide, and the walls of the
          entrance were.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: '  After that, the man brought me into the sanctuary of the Temple.
        He measured the walls on either side of its doorway,[[COMMENT(0)]] and they
        were 10-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] thick. '
      comments:
      - number: '41:1a '
        content: As in Greek version; the meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
      - number: '41:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>6 cubits </b>[3.2 meters]; also in 41:3, 5.
    - title: 
      content: 'The doorway was 17-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] wide, and the walls on
        each side of it were 8-3/4 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] long. The sanctuary itself
        was 70 feet long and 35 feet wide.[[COMMENT(2)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '41:2a '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[5.3 meters].
      - number: '41:2b '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.7 meters]; also in 41:9, 11.
      - number: '41:2c '
        content: Hebrew <b>40 cubits </b>[21.2 meters] <b>long and 20 cubits </b>[10.6
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he went beyond the sanctuary into the inner room. He measured
        the walls on either side of its entrance, and they were 3-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        thick. The entrance was 10-1/2 feet wide, and the walls on each side of the
        entrance were 12-1/4 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] long. '
      comments:
      - number: '41:3a '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 cubits </b>[1.1 meters].
      - number: '41:3b '
        content: Hebrew <b>7 cubits </b>[3.7 meters].
    - title: 
      content: "The inner room of the sanctuary was 35 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] long and
        35 feet wide. \u201CThis,\u201D he told me, \u201Cis the Most Holy Place.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '41:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>20 cubits </b>[10.6 meters]; also in 41:4b, 10.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he measured the wall of the Temple, and it was 10-1/2 feet thick.
        There was a row of rooms along the outside wall; each room was 7 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide. '
      comments:
      - number: '41:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>4 cubits </b>[2.1 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'These side rooms were built in three levels, one above the other,
        with thirty rooms on each level. The supports for these side rooms rested
        on exterior ledges on the Temple wall; they did not extend into the wall. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each level was wider than the one below it, corresponding to the
        narrowing of the Temple wall as it rose higher. A stairway led up from the
        bottom level through the middle level to the top level.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I saw that the Temple was built on a terrace, which provided a foundation
        for the side rooms. This terrace was 10-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] high. '
      comments:
      - number: '41:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 rod, 6 cubits </b>[3.2 meters].
    - title: 
      content: "The outer wall of the Temple\u2019s side rooms was 8-3/4 feet thick.
        This left an open area between these side rooms "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and the row of rooms along the outer wall of the inner courtyard.
        This open area was 35 feet wide, and it went all the way around the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Two doors opened from the side rooms into the terrace yard, which
        was 8-3/4 feet wide. One door faced north and the other south.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A large building stood on the west, facing the Temple courtyard.
        It was 122-1/2 feet wide and 157-1/2 feet long, and its walls were 8-3/4
        feet[[COMMENT(0)]] thick. '
      comments:
      - number: '41:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>70 cubits </b>[37.1 meters] <b>wide and 90 cubits </b>[47.7
          meters] <b>long, and its walls were 5 cubits </b>[2.7 meters] <b>thick.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the man measured the Temple, and it was 175 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        long. The courtyard around the building, including its walls, was an additional
        175 feet in length. '
      comments:
      - number: '41:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 cubits </b>[53 meters]; also in 41:13b, 14, 15.
    - title: 
      content: 'The inner courtyard to the east of the Temple was also 175 feet wide. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The building to the west, including its two walls, was also 175 feet
        wide.The sanctuary, the inner room, and the entry room of the Temple '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'were all paneled with wood, as were the frames of the recessed windows.
        The inner walls of the Temple were paneled with wood above and below the
        windows. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The space above the door leading into the inner room, and its walls
        inside and out, were also paneled. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the walls were decorated with carvings of cherubim, each with
        two faces, and there was a carving of a palm tree between each of the cherubim. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One face\u2014that of a man\u2014looked toward the palm tree on one
        side. The other face\u2014that of a young lion\u2014looked toward the palm
        tree on the other side. The figures were carved all along the inside of the
        Temple, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'from the floor to the top of the walls, including the outer wall
        of the sanctuary.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There were square columns at the entrance to the sanctuary, and the
        ones at the entrance of the Most Holy Place were similar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There was an altar made of wood, 5-1/4 feet high and 3-1/2 feet across.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Its corners, base, and sides were all made of wood. \u201CThis,\u201D the
        man told me, \u201Cis the table that stands in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        presence.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '41:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>3 cubits </b>[1.6 meters] <b>high and 2 cubits </b>[1.1
          meters] <b>across.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Both the sanctuary and the Most Holy Place had double doorways, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'each with two swinging doors. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The doors leading into the sanctuary were decorated with carved cherubim
        and palm trees, just as on the walls. And there was a wooden roof at the
        front of the entry room to the Temple. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Rooms for the Priests
      content: '  Then the man led me out of the Temple courtyard by way of the north
        gateway. We entered the outer courtyard and came to a group of rooms against
        the north wall of the inner courtyard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This structure, whose entrance opened toward the north, was 175 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        long and 87-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] wide. '
      comments:
      - number: '42:2a '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 cubits </b>[53 meters]; also in 42:8.
      - number: '42:2b '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 cubits </b>[26.5 meters]; also in 42:7, 8.
    - title: 
      content: 'One block of rooms overlooked the 35-foot[[COMMENT(0)]] width of
        the inner courtyard. Another block of rooms looked out onto the pavement
        of the outer courtyard. The two blocks were built three levels high and stood
        across from each other. '
      comments:
      - number: '42:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>20[-cubit] </b>[10.6-meter].
    - title: 
      content: 'Between the two blocks of rooms ran a walkway 17-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        wide. It extended the entire 175 feet of the complex,[[COMMENT(1)]] and all
        the doors faced north. '
      comments:
      - number: '42:4a '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[5.3 meters].
      - number: '42:4b '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions, which read <b>Its length was 100
          cubits </b>[53 meters]; Hebrew reads <b>and a passage 1 cubit </b>[21 inches
          or 53 centimeters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Each of the two upper levels of rooms was narrower than the one beneath
        it because the upper levels had to allow space for walkways in front of them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Since there were three levels and they did not have supporting columns
        as in the courtyards, each of the upper levels was set back from the level
        beneath it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was an outer wall that separated the rooms from the outer courtyard;
        it was 87-1/2 feet long. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This wall added length to the outer block of rooms, which extended
        for only 87-1/2 feet, while the inner block\u2014the rooms toward the Temple\u2014extended
        for 175 feet. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was an eastern entrance from the outer courtyard to these rooms.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the south[[COMMENT(0)]] side of the Temple there were two blocks
        of rooms just south of the inner courtyard between the Temple and the outer
        courtyard. These rooms were arranged just like the rooms on the north. '
      comments:
      - number: '42:10 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>east.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'There was a walkway between the two blocks of rooms just like the
        complex on the north side of the Temple. This complex of rooms was the same
        length and width as the other one, and it had the same entrances and doors.
        The dimensions of each were identical. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So there was an entrance in the wall facing the doors of the inner
        block of rooms, and another on the east at the end of the interior walkway.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the man told me, \u201CThese rooms that overlook the Temple
        from the north and south are holy. Here the priests who offer sacrifices
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will eat the most holy offerings. And
        because these rooms are holy, they will be used to store the sacred offerings\u2014the
        grain offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the priests leave the sanctuary, they must not go directly to
        the outer courtyard. They must first take off the clothes they wore while
        ministering, because these clothes are holy. They must put on other clothes
        before entering the parts of the building complex open to the public.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the man had finished measuring the inside of the Temple area,
        he led me out through the east gateway to measure the entire perimeter. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He measured the east side with his measuring rod, and it was 875
        feet long.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '42:16 '
        content: As in 45:2 and in Greek version at 42:17, which reads <b>500 cubits
          </b>[265 meters]; Hebrew reads <b>500 rods </b>[5,250 feet or 1,590 meters];
          similarly in 42:17, 18, 19, 20.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he measured the north side, and it was also 875 feet. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The south side was also 875 feet, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and the west side was also 875 feet. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Glory Returns"
      content: '  After this, the man brought me back around to the east gateway. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Suddenly, the glory of the God of Israel appeared from the east.
        The sound of his coming was like the roar of rushing waters, and the whole
        landscape shone with his glory. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This vision was just like the others I had seen, first by the Kebar
        River and then when he came[[COMMENT(0)]] to destroy Jerusalem. I fell face
        down on the ground. '
      comments:
      - number: '43:3 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Latin Vulgate; Masoretic Text
          reads <b>I came.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'And the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came into the Temple
        through the east gateway.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the Spirit took me up and brought me into the inner courtyard,
        and the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> filled the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I heard someone speaking to me from within the Temple, while
        the man who had been measuring stood beside me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CSon of man, this
        is the place of my throne and the place where I will rest my feet. I will
        live here forever among the people of Israel. They and their kings will not
        defile my holy name any longer by their adulterous worship of other gods
        or by honoring the relics of their kings who have died.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '43:7 '
        content: Or <b>kings on their high places.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'They put their idol altars right next to mine with only a wall between
        them and me. They defiled my holy name by such detestable sin, so I consumed
        them in my anger. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now let them stop worshiping other gods and honoring the relics of
        their kings, and I will live among them forever.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSon of man, describe to the people of Israel the Temple I have
        shown you, so they will be ashamed of all their sins. Let them study its
        plan, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and they will be ashamed[[COMMENT(0)]] of what they have done. Describe
        to them all the specifications of the Temple\u2014including its entrances
        and exits\u2014and everything else about it. Tell them about its decrees
        and laws. Write down all these specifications and decrees as they watch so
        they will be sure to remember and follow them. "
      comments:
      - number: '43:11 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>if they are ashamed.</b>
    - title: The Altar
      content: 'And this is the basic law of the Temple: absolute holiness! The entire
        top of the mountain where the Temple is built is holy. Yes, this is the basic
        law of the Temple.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese are the measurements of the altar[[COMMENT(0)]]: There
        is a gutter all around the altar 21 inches deep and 21 inches wide,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        with a curb 9 inches[[COMMENT(2)]] wide around its edge. And this is the
        height[[COMMENT(3)]] of the altar: "
      comments:
      - number: '43:13a '
        content: Hebrew <b>measurements of the altar in long cubits, each being a
          cubit </b>[18 inches or 45 centimeters] <b>and a handbreadth </b>[3 inches
          or 8 centimeters] <b>in length.</b>
      - number: '43:13b '
        content: Hebrew <b>a cubit </b>[53 centimeters] <b>deep and a cubit wide.</b>
      - number: '43:13c '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 span </b>[23 centimeters].
      - number: '43:13d '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>base.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'From the gutter the altar rises 3-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] to a lower
        ledge that surrounds the altar and is 21 inches[[COMMENT(1)]] wide. From
        the lower ledge the altar rises 7 feet[[COMMENT(2)]] to the upper ledge that
        is also 21 inches wide. '
      comments:
      - number: '43:14a '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 cubits </b>[1.1 meters].
      - number: '43:14b '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 cubit </b>[53 centimeters]; also in 43:14d.
      - number: '43:14c '
        content: Hebrew <b>4 cubits </b>[2.1 meters]; also in 43:15.
    - title: 
      content: 'The top of the altar, the hearth, rises another 7 feet higher, with
        a horn rising up from each of the four corners. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The top of the altar is square, measuring 21 feet by 21 feet.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '43:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>12 [cubits] </b>[6.4 meters] <b>long and 12 [cubits] wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "The upper ledge also forms a square, measuring 24-1/2 feet by 24-1/2
        feet,[[COMMENT(0)]] with a 21-inch gutter and a 10-1/2-inch curb[[COMMENT(1)]]
        all around the edge. There are steps going up the east side of the altar.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '43:17a '
        content: Hebrew <b>14 [cubits] </b>[7.4 meters] <b>long and 14 [cubits] wide.</b>
      - number: '43:17b '
        content: Hebrew <b>a gutter of 1 cubit </b>[53 centimeters] <b>and a curb
          of 1/2 a cubit </b>[27 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CSon of man, this is what the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: These will be the regulations for the burning
        of offerings and the sprinkling of blood when the altar is built. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At that time, the Levitical priests of the family of Zadok, who minister
        before me, are to be given a young bull for a sin offering, says the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You will take some of its blood and smear it on the four horns of
        the altar, the four corners of the upper ledge, and the curb that runs around
        that ledge. This will cleanse and make atonement for the altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then take the young bull for the sin offering and burn it at the
        appointed place outside the Temple area.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COn the second day, sacrifice as a sin offering a young male
        goat that has no physical defects. Then cleanse and make atonement for the
        altar again, just as you did with the young bull. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When you have finished the cleansing ceremony, offer another young
        bull that has no defects and a perfect ram from the flock. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You are to present them to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and the
        priests are to sprinkle salt on them and offer them as a burnt offering to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEvery day for seven days a male goat, a young bull, and a ram
        from the flock will be sacrificed as a sin offering. None of these animals
        may have physical defects of any kind. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Do this each day for seven days to cleanse and make atonement for
        the altar, thus setting it apart for holy use. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Prince, Levites, and Priests
      content: '  Then the man brought me back to the east gateway in the outer wall
        of the Temple area, but it was closed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CThis gate must
        remain closed; it will never again be opened. No one will ever open it and
        pass through, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, has
        entered here. Therefore, it must always remain shut. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Only the prince himself may sit inside this gateway to feast in the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence. But he may come and go only
        through the entry room of the gateway.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the man brought me through the north gateway to the front of
        the Temple. I looked and saw that the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        filled the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and I fell face down
        on the ground.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to me, \u201CSon of man,
        take careful notice. Use your eyes and ears, and listen to everything I tell
        you about the regulations concerning the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. Take careful note of the procedures for using the Temple\u2019s entrances
        and exits. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And give these rebels, the people of Israel, this message from the
        Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: O people of Israel, enough of your
        detestable sins! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You have brought uncircumcised foreigners into my sanctuary\u2014people
        who have no heart for God. In this way, you defiled my Temple even as you
        offered me my food, the fat and blood of sacrifices. In addition to all your
        other detestable sins, you have broken my covenant. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instead of safeguarding my sacred rituals, you have hired foreigners
        to take charge of my sanctuary.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        No foreigners, including those who live among the people of Israel, will
        enter my sanctuary if they have not been circumcised and have not surrendered
        themselves to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the men of the tribe of Levi who abandoned me when Israel strayed
        away from me to worship idols[[COMMENT(0)]] must bear the consequences of
        their unfaithfulness. '
      comments:
      - number: '44:10 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung; also in 44:12.
    - title: 
      content: 'They may still be Temple guards and gatekeepers, and they may slaughter
        the animals brought for burnt offerings and be present to help the people. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But they encouraged my people to worship idols, causing Israel to
        fall into deep sin. So I have taken a solemn oath that they must bear the
        consequences for their sins, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They may not approach me to minister as priests. They may not touch
        any of my holy things or the holy offerings, for they must bear the shame
        of all the detestable sins they have committed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They are to serve as the Temple caretakers, taking charge of the
        maintenance work and performing general duties.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHowever, the Levitical priests of the family of Zadok continued
        to minister faithfully in the Temple when Israel abandoned me for idols.
        These men will serve as my ministers. They will stand in my presence and
        offer the fat and blood of the sacrifices, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They alone will enter my sanctuary and approach my table to serve
        me. They will fulfill all my requirements.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen they enter the gateway to the inner courtyard, they must
        wear only linen clothing. They must wear no wool while on duty in the inner
        courtyard or in the Temple itself. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They must wear linen turbans and linen undergarments. They must not
        wear anything that would cause them to perspire. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they return to the outer courtyard where the people are, they
        must take off the clothes they wear while ministering to me. They must leave
        them in the sacred rooms and put on other clothes so they do not endanger
        anyone by transmitting holiness to them through this clothing.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThey must neither shave their heads nor let their hair grow
        too long. Instead, they must trim it regularly. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The priests must not drink wine before entering the inner courtyard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They may choose their wives only from among the virgins of Israel
        or the widows of the priests. They may not marry other widows or divorced
        women. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will teach my people the difference between what is holy and
        what is common, what is ceremonially clean and unclean.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThey will serve as judges to resolve any disagreements among
        my people. Their decisions must be based on my regulations. And the priests
        themselves must obey my instructions and decrees at all the sacred festivals,
        and see to it that the Sabbaths are set apart as holy days.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CA priest must not defile himself by being in the presence of
        a dead person unless it is his father, mother, child, brother, or unmarried
        sister. In such cases it is permitted. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even then, he can return to his Temple duties only after being ceremonially
        cleansed and then waiting for seven days. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The first day he returns to work and enters the inner courtyard and
        the sanctuary, he must offer a sin offering for himself, says the Sovereign
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe priests will not have any property or possession of land,
        for I alone am their special possession. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Their food will come from the gifts and sacrifices brought to the
        Temple by the people\u2014the grain offerings, the sin offerings, and the
        guilt offerings. Whatever anyone sets apart[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> for
        the </smallcaps><smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will belong to the priests. "
      comments:
      - number: '44:29 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering.
    - title: 
      content: 'The first of the ripe fruits and all the gifts brought to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will go to the priests. The first batch of dough must also be given to the
        priests so the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will bless your homes. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Division of the Land
      content: "  \u201CWhen you divide the land among the tribes of Israel, you
        must set aside a section for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as his holy
        portion. This piece of land will be 8-1/3 miles long and 6-2/3 miles wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        The entire area will be holy. "
      comments:
      - number: '45:1 '
        content: As in Greek version, which reads <b>25,000 [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers]
          <b>long and 20,000 [cubits] </b>[10.6 kilometers] <b>wide; </b>Hebrew reads
          <b>25,000 [cubits] long and 10,000 [cubits] </b>[3-1/3 miles or 5.3 kilometers]
          <b>wide. </b>Compare 45:3, 5; 48:9.
    - title: 
      content: 'A section of this land, measuring 875 feet by 875 feet,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        will be set aside for the Temple. An additional strip of land 87-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(1)]]
        wide is to be left empty all around it. '
      comments:
      - number: '45:2a '
        content: Hebrew <b>500 [cubits] </b>[265 meters] <b>by 500 [cubits], a square.</b>
      - number: '45:2b '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 cubits </b>[26.5 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Within the larger sacred area, measure out a portion of land 8-1/3
        miles long and 3-1/3 miles wide.[[COMMENT(0)]] Within it the sanctuary of
        the Most Holy Place will be located. '
      comments:
      - number: '45:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>25,000 [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers] <b>long and 10,000
          [cubits] </b>[5.3 kilometers] <b>wide; </b>also in 45:5.
    - title: 
      content: 'This area will be holy, set aside for the priests who minister to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> in the sanctuary. They will use it for their
        homes, and my Temple will be located within it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The strip of sacred land next to it, also 8-1/3 miles long and 3-1/3
        miles wide, will be a living area for the Levites who work at the Temple.
        It will be their possession and a place for their towns.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:5 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>They will have as their possession
          20 rooms.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAdjacent to the larger sacred area will be a section of land
        8-1/3 miles long and 1-2/3 miles wide.[[COMMENT(0)]] This will be set aside
        for a city where anyone in Israel can live.  "
      comments:
      - number: '45:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>25,000 [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers] <b>long and 5,000
          [cubits] </b>[2.65 kilometers] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTwo special sections of land will be set apart for the prince.
        One section will share a border with the east side of the sacred lands and
        city, and the second section will share a border on the west side. Then the
        far eastern and western borders of the prince\u2019s lands will line up with
        the eastern and western boundaries of the tribal areas. "
      comments: []
    - title: Rules for the Princes
      content: "These sections of land will be the prince\u2019s allotment. Then
        my princes will no longer oppress and rob my people; they will assign the
        rest of the land to the people, giving an allotment to each tribe.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor this is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Enough, you princes of Israel! Stop your violence and oppression and
        do what is just and right. Quit robbing and cheating my people out of their
        land. Stop expelling them from their homes, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Use only honest weights and scales and honest measures, both dry
        and liquid.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Use honest scales, an honest ephah, and an honest bath.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The homer[[COMMENT(0)]] will be your standard unit for measuring
        volume. The ephah and the bath[[COMMENT(1)]] will each measure one-tenth
        of a homer. '
      comments:
      - number: '45:11a '
        content: The <b>homer </b>measures about 50 gallons or 220 liters.
      - number: '45:11b '
        content: The <b>ephah </b>is a dry measure; the <b>bath </b>is a liquid measure.
    - title: Special Offerings and Celebrations
      content: 'The standard unit for weight will be the silver shekel.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        One shekel will consist of twenty gerahs, and sixty shekels will be equal
        to one mina.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:12a '
        content: The <b>shekel </b>weighs about 0.4 ounces or 11 grams.
      - number: '45:12b '
        content: Elsewhere the <b>mina </b>is equated to 50 shekels.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must give this tax to the prince: one bushel of wheat or
        barley for every 60[[COMMENT(0)]] you harvest, "
      comments:
      - number: '45:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1/6 of an ephah from each homer of wheat and 1/6 of an
          ephah from each homer of barley.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'one percent of your olive oil,[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the portion of oil, measured by the bath, is 1/10 of a
          bath from each cor, which consists of 10 baths or 1 homer, for 10 baths
          are equivalent to a homer.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'and one sheep or goat for every 200 in your flocks in Israel. These
        will be the grain offerings, burnt offerings, and peace offerings that will
        make atonement for the people who bring them, says the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the people of Israel must join in bringing these offerings to
        the prince. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The prince will be required to provide offerings that are given at
        the religious festivals, the new moon celebrations, the Sabbath days, and
        all other similar occasions. He will provide the sin offerings, burnt offerings,
        grain offerings, liquid offerings, and peace offerings to purify the people
        of Israel, making them right with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:17 '
        content: Or <b>to make atonement for the people of Israel.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        In early spring, on the first day of each new year,[[COMMENT(0)]] sacrifice
        a young bull with no defects to purify the Temple. "
      comments:
      - number: '45:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the first month, </b>of the Hebrew
          calendar. This day in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in March
          or April.
    - title: 
      content: 'The priest will take blood from this sin offering and put it on the
        doorposts of the Temple, the four corners of the upper ledge of the altar,
        and the gateposts at the entrance to the inner courtyard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Do this also on the seventh day of the new year for anyone who has
        sinned through error or ignorance. In this way, you will purify[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the Temple.  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:20 '
        content: Or <b>will make atonement for.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COn the fourteenth day of the first month,[[COMMENT(0)]] you
        must celebrate the Passover. This festival will last for seven days. The
        bread you eat during that time must be made without yeast. "
      comments:
      - number: '45:21 '
        content: This day in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in late March,
          April, or early May.
    - title: 
      content: 'On the day of Passover the prince will provide a young bull as a
        sin offering for himself and the people of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On each of the seven days of the feast he will prepare a burnt offering
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, consisting of seven young bulls and seven
        rams without defects. A male goat will also be given each day for a sin offering. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The prince will provide a basket of flour as a grain offering and
        a gallon of olive oil[[COMMENT(0)]] with each young bull and ram.  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>an ephah </b>[20 quarts or 22 liters] <b>of flour . .
          . and a hin </b>[3.8 liters] <b>of olive oil.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  \u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        The east gateway of the inner courtyard will be closed during the six workdays
        each week, but it will be open on Sabbath days and the days of new moon celebrations. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The prince will enter the entry room of the gateway from the outside.
        Then he will stand by the gatepost while the priest offers his burnt offering
        and peace offering. He will bow down in worship inside the gateway passage
        and then go back out the way he came. The gateway will not be closed until
        evening. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The common people will bow down and worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in front of this gateway on Sabbath days and the days of new moon celebrations.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEach Sabbath day the prince will present to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        a burnt offering of six lambs and one ram, all with no defects. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He will present a grain offering of a basket of choice flour to go
        with the ram and whatever amount of flour he chooses to go with each lamb,
        and he is to offer one gallon of olive oil[[COMMENT(0)]] for each basket
        of flour. '
      comments:
      - number: '46:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>an ephah </b>[20 quarts or 22 liters] <b>of choice flour
          . . . a hin </b>[3.8 liters] <b>of olive oil; </b>similarly in 46:7, 11.
    - title: 
      content: 'At the new moon celebrations, he will bring one young bull, six lambs,
        and one ram, all with no defects. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'With the young bull he must bring a basket of choice flour for a
        grain offering. With the ram he must bring another basket of flour. And with
        each lamb he is to bring whatever amount of flour he chooses to give. With
        each basket of flour he must offer one gallon of olive oil.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe prince must enter the gateway through the entry room, and
        he must leave the same way. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the people come in through the north gateway to worship
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> during the religious festivals, they must
        leave by the south gateway. And those who entered through the south gateway
        must leave by the north gateway. They must never leave by the same gateway
        they came in, but must always use the opposite gateway. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The prince will enter and leave with the people on these occasions.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo at the special feasts and sacred festivals, the grain offering
        will be a basket of choice flour with each young bull, another basket of
        flour with each ram, and as much flour as the worshiper chooses to give with
        each lamb. Give one gallon of olive oil with each basket of flour. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the prince offers a voluntary burnt offering or peace offering
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the east gateway to the inner courtyard
        will be opened for him, and he will offer his sacrifices as he does on Sabbath
        days. Then he will leave, and the gateway will be shut behind him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEach morning you must sacrifice a one-year-old lamb with no
        defects as a burnt offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "With the lamb, a grain offering must also be given to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014about
        three quarts of flour with a third of a gallon of olive oil[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to moisten the choice flour. This will be a permanent law for you. "
      comments:
      - number: '46:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1/6 of an ephah </b>[3.7 liters] <b>of flour with 1/3
          of a hin </b>[1.3 liters] <b>of olive oil.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The lamb, the grain offering, and the olive oil must be given as
        a daily sacrifice every morning without fail.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        If the prince gives a gift of land to one of his sons as his inheritance,
        it will belong to him and his descendants forever. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if the prince gives a gift of land from his inheritance to one
        of his servants, the servant may keep it only until the Year of Jubilee,
        which comes every fiftieth year.[[COMMENT(0)]] At that time the land will
        return to the prince. But when the prince gives gifts to his sons, those
        gifts will be permanent. '
      comments:
      - number: '46:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>until the Year of Release; </b>see Lev 25:8-17.
    - title: The Temple Kitchens
      content: "And the prince may never take anyone\u2019s property by force. If
        he gives property to his sons, it must be from his own land, for I do not
        want any of my people unjustly evicted from their property.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In my vision, the man brought me through the entrance beside the
        gateway and led me to the sacred rooms assigned to the priests, which faced
        toward the north. He showed me a place at the extreme west end of these rooms. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He explained, \u201CThis is where the priests will cook the meat
        from the guilt offerings and sin offerings and bake the flour from the grain
        offerings into bread. They will do it here to avoid carrying the sacrifices
        through the outer courtyard and endangering the people by transmitting holiness
        to them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he brought me back to the outer courtyard and led me to each
        of its four corners. In each corner I saw an enclosure. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each of these enclosures was 70 feet long and 52-1/2 feet wide,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        surrounded by walls. '
      comments:
      - number: '46:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>40 [cubits] </b>[21.2 meters] <b>long and 30 [cubits]
          </b>[15.9 meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Along the inside of these walls was a ledge of stone with fireplaces
        under the ledge all the way around. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The River of Healing
      content: '  In my vision, the man brought me back to the entrance of the Temple.
        There I saw a stream flowing east from beneath the door of the Temple and
        passing to the right of the altar on its south side. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The man brought me outside the wall through the north gateway and
        led me around to the eastern entrance. There I could see the water flowing
        out through the south side of the east gateway.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Measuring as he went, he took me along the stream for 1,750 feet[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and then led me across. The water was up to my ankles. '
      comments:
      - number: '47:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1,000 cubits </b>[530 meters]; also in 47:4, 5.
    - title: 
      content: 'He measured off another 1,750 feet and led me across again. This
        time the water was up to my knees. After another 1,750 feet, it was up to
        my waist. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he measured another 1,750 feet, and the river was too deep to
        walk across. It was deep enough to swim in, but too deep to walk through.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He asked me, \u201CHave you been watching, son of man?\u201D Then
        he led me back along the riverbank. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I returned, I was surprised by the sight of many trees growing
        on both sides of the river. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CThis river flows east through the desert
        into the valley of the Dead Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]] The waters of this stream
        will make the salty waters of the Dead Sea fresh and pure. "
      comments:
      - number: '47:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'There will be swarms of living things wherever the water of this
        river flows.[[COMMENT(0)]] Fish will abound in the Dead Sea, for its waters
        will become fresh. Life will flourish wherever this water flows. '
      comments:
      - number: '47:9 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads <b>of these two rivers
          flow.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Fishermen will stand along the shores of the Dead Sea. All the way
        from En-gedi to En-eglaim, the shores will be covered with nets drying in
        the sun. Fish of every kind will fill the Dead Sea, just as they fill the
        Mediterranean.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '47:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Great Sea; </b>also in 47:15, 17, 19, 20.
    - title: 
      content: 'But the marshes and swamps will not be purified; they will still
        be salty. '
      comments: []
    - title: Boundaries for the Land
      content: "Fruit trees of all kinds will grow along both sides of the river.
        The leaves of these trees will never turn brown and fall, and there will
        always be fruit on their branches. There will be a new crop every month,
        for they are watered by the river flowing from the Temple. The fruit will
        be for food and the leaves for healing.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is what the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: \u201CDivide
        the land in this way for the twelve tribes of Israel: The descendants of
        Joseph will be given two shares of land.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '47:13 '
        content: "It was important to retain twelve portions of land. Since Levi
          had no portion, the descendants of Joseph\u2019s sons, Ephraim and Manasseh,
          received land as two tribes."
    - title: 
      content: 'Otherwise each tribe will receive an equal share. I took a solemn
        oath and swore that I would give this land to your ancestors, and it will
        now come to you as your possession.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese are the boundaries of the land: The northern border will
        run from the Mediterranean toward Hethlon, then on through Lebo-hamath to
        Zedad; "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'then it will run to Berothah and Sibraim,[[COMMENT(0)]] which are
        on the border between Damascus and Hamath, and finally to Hazer-hatticon,
        on the border of Hauran. '
      comments:
      - number: '47:15-16 '
        content: As in Greek version; Masoretic Text reads <b>then on through Lebo
          to Zedad; </b><b>then it will run to Hamath, Berothah, and Sibraim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So the northern border will run from the Mediterranean to Hazar-enan,
        on the border between Hamath to the north and Damascus to the south.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe eastern border starts at a point between Hauran and Damascus
        and runs south along the Jordan River between Israel and Gilead, past the
        Dead Sea[[COMMENT(0)]] and as far south as Tamar.[[COMMENT(1)]] This will
        be the eastern border.  "
      comments:
      - number: '47:18a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the eastern sea.</b>
      - number: '47:18b '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>you will measure.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe southern border will go west from Tamar to the waters of
        Meribah at Kadesh[[COMMENT(0)]] and then follow the course of the Brook of
        Egypt to the Mediterranean. This will be the southern border.  "
      comments:
      - number: '47:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>waters of Meribath-kadesh.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COn the west side, the Mediterranean itself will be your border
        from the southern border to the point where the northern border begins, opposite
        Lebo-hamath.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDivide the land within these boundaries among the tribes of
        Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Distribute the land as an allotment for yourselves and for the foreigners
        who have joined you and are raising their families among you. They will be
        like native-born Israelites to you and will receive an allotment among the
        tribes. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Division of the Land
      content: "  \u201CHere is the list of the tribes of Israel and the territory
        each is to receive. The territory of Dan is in the extreme north. Its boundary
        line follows the Hethlon road to Lebo-hamath and then runs on to Hazar-enan
        on the border of Damascus, with Hamath to the north. Dan\u2019s territory
        extends all the way across the land of Israel from east to west.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAsher\u2019s territory lies south of Dan\u2019s and also extends
        from east to west. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Naphtali\u2019s land lies south of Asher\u2019s, also extending from
        east to west. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then comes Manasseh south of Naphtali, and its territory also extends
        from east to west. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'South of Manasseh is Ephraim, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and then Reuben, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and then Judah, all of whose boundaries extend from east to west.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSouth of Judah is the land set aside for a special purpose.
        It will be 8-1/3 miles[[COMMENT(0)]] wide and will extend as far east and
        west as the tribal territories, with the Temple at the center.  "
      comments:
      - number: '48:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>25,000 [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers].
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe area set aside for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple will be 8-1/3 miles long and 6-2/3 miles wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '48:9 '
        content: 'As in one Greek manuscript and the Greek reading in 45:1: <b>25,000
          [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers] <b>long and 20,000 [cubits] </b>[10.6 kilometers]
          <b>wide; </b>Hebrew reads <b>25,000 [cubits] long and 10,000 [cubits] </b>[3-1/3
          miles or 5.3 kilometers] <b>wide. </b>Similarly in 48:13b. Compare 45:1-5;
          48:10-13.'
    - title: 
      content: "For the priests there will be a strip of land measuring 8-1/3 miles
        long by 3-1/3 miles wide,[[COMMENT(0)]] with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple at the center. "
      comments:
      - number: '48:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>25,000 [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers] <b>long by 10,000
          [cubits] </b>[5.3 kilometers] <b>wide; </b>also in 48:13a.
    - title: 
      content: 'This area is set aside for the ordained priests, the descendants
        of Zadok who served me faithfully and did not go astray with the people of
        Israel and the rest of the Levites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It will be their special portion when the land is distributed, the
        most sacred land of all. Next to the priests\u2019 territory will lie the
        land where the other Levites will live.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe land allotted to the Levites will be the same size and
        shape as that belonging to the priests\u20148-1/3 miles long and 3-1/3 miles
        wide. Together these portions of land will measure 8-1/3 miles long by 6-2/3
        miles wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '48:13 '
        content: See note on 48:9.
    - title: 
      content: 'None of this special land may ever be sold or traded or used by others,
        for it belongs to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>; it is set apart as holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAn additional strip of land 8-1/3 miles long by 1-2/3 miles
        wide,[[COMMENT(0)]] south of the sacred Temple area, will be allotted for
        public use\u2014homes, pasturelands, and common lands, with a city at the
        center. "
      comments:
      - number: '48:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>25,000 [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers] <b>long by 5,000
          [cubits] </b>[2.65 kilometers] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "The city will measure 1-1/2 miles[[COMMENT(0)]] on each side\u2014north,
        south, east, and west. "
      comments:
      - number: '48:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>4,500 [cubits] </b>[2.4 kilometers]; also in 48:30, 32,
          33, 34.
    - title: 
      content: 'Open lands will surround the city for 150 yards[[COMMENT(0)]] in
        every direction. '
      comments:
      - number: '48:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>250 [cubits] </b>[133 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Outside the city there will be a farming area that stretches 3-1/3
        miles to the east and 3-1/3 miles to the west[[COMMENT(0)]] along the border
        of the sacred area. This farmland will produce food for the people working
        in the city. '
      comments:
      - number: '48:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10,000 [cubits] </b>[5.3 kilometers] <b>to the east and
          10,000 [cubits] to the west.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Those who come from the various tribes to work in the city may farm
        it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This entire area\u2014including the sacred lands and the city\u2014is
        a square that measures 8-1/3 miles[[COMMENT(0)]] on each side.  "
      comments:
      - number: '48:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>25,000 [cubits] </b>[13.3 kilometers]; also in 48:21.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe areas that remain, to the east and to the west of the sacred
        lands and the city, will belong to the prince. Each of these areas will be
        8-1/3 miles wide, extending in opposite directions to the eastern and western
        borders of Israel, with the sacred lands and the sanctuary of the Temple
        in the center. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the prince\u2019s land will include everything between the territories
        allotted to Judah and Benjamin, except for the areas set aside for the sacred
        lands and the city.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese are the territories allotted to the rest of the tribes.
        Benjamin\u2019s territory lies just south of the prince\u2019s lands, and
        it extends across the entire land of Israel from east to west. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "South of Benjamin\u2019s territory lies that of Simeon, also extending
        across the land from east to west. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next is the territory of Issachar with the same eastern and western
        boundaries.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen comes the territory of Zebulun, which also extends across
        the land from east to west. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The territory of Gad is just south of Zebulun with the same borders
        to the east and west. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The southern border of Gad runs from Tamar to the waters of Meribah
        at Kadesh[[COMMENT(0)]] and then follows the Brook of Egypt to the Mediterranean.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '48:28a '
        content: Hebrew <b>waters of Meribath-kadesh.</b>
      - number: '48:28b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Great Sea.</b>
    - title: The Gates of the City
      content: "\u201CThese are the allotments that will be set aside for each tribe\u2019s
        exclusive possession. I, the Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, have
        spoken!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese will be the exits to the city: On the north wall, which
        is 1-1/2 miles long, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'there will be three gates, each one named after a tribe of Israel.
        The first will be named for Reuben, the second for Judah, and the third for
        Levi. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the east wall, also 1-1/2 miles long, the gates will be named
        for Joseph, Benjamin, and Dan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The south wall, also 1-1/2 miles long, will have gates named for
        Simeon, Issachar, and Zebulun. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And on the west wall, also 1-1/2 miles long, the gates will be named
        for Gad, Asher, and Naphtali.  '
      comments: []
